\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
My Thesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Tomomi Sunayama
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
correlation functions and power spectra
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Reconstruction of Real-space Density from Redshift-space density
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Redshift-space distortions (hereafter RSDs) are a systematic anisotropy
 in galaxy distribution and are used as a dynamical probe of Cosmic Acceleration.
 By the cosmological principle, the distribution of galaxies is statistically
 isotropic (on large scales).
 The positions of galaxies are, however, measured through redshifts, which
 generates anisotropy in observed galaxy distributions due to line-of-sight
 (hereafter, LOS) peculiar velocities of galaxies.
 The effects of RSDs are seen on both small and large scales, and are known
 as the Finger-of-God effect (hereafter FoG) and the squashing effect.
 The FoG effect is due to random motions of galaxies in a virialized halo,
 while the squashing effect is caused by gravitational infall motion of
 clusters.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The squashing effect was first modeled by Kaiser 1987 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1987MNRAS.227....1K"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1992ApJ...385L...5H"

\end_inset

 in configuration-space) using linear perturbation theory and called the
 Kaiser approximation.
 It provides a way to measure the growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $f\approx\Omega_{m}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 to test the model of gravity as well as the expansion history of the Universe.
 The challenge in the measurement of the growth rate is that the Kaiser
 approximation is valid only on very large scales and therefore suffers
 from sample variance.
 In order to avoid this problem, there have been many attempts to model
 RSDs beyond linear theory both in configuration-space and Fourier-space
 by using the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

streaming model
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1995AAS...186.2904F,2009MNRAS.393..297P,2011MNRAS.417.1913R,2010PhRvD..82f3522T,2011ApJ...726....5O,1994ApJ...421L...1N"

\end_inset

), using Halo Occupation Distribution to model pairwise velocities of galaxies
 in terms of halo mass (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1999MNRAS.310.1137H,2006MNRAS.368...85T,2007MNRAS.374..477T"

\end_inset

), and extending the model of RSDs to higher-order terms(
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2004PhRvD..70h3007S,2008Natur.451..541G,2010PhRvD..82f3522T,2011JCAP...11..039S,2011MNRAS.410.2081J,2011PhRvD..84d3526N,2012JCAP...02..010O"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, there have been many studies attempting to recover real-space
 density field or primordial density fluctuation from the redshift-space
 density field (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1989ApJ...344L..53P,1991ApJ...379....6N,1993ApJ...405L..47G,1994ApJ...421L...1N,1997MNRAS.285..793C,1998ApJ...508..440N,1999ApJ...515..471N,2012arXiv1203.5785T"

\end_inset

).

\color black
 Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1994ApJ...421L...1N"

\end_inset

 proposed a way to recover real-space density from redshift-space density
 through Lagrangian perturbation theory (LPT).
 They estimated peculiar velocity fields of particles and shifted back the
 particles in redshift-space by their velocities to reconstruct a real-space
 density field.

\color blue
 
\color inherit
In this project, we measured 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 using LPT by reconstructing the density field in real-space from the one
 in redshift-space.
 While 
\color black
Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1994ApJ...421L...1N"

\end_inset

 
\color inherit
used a fixed value for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to model the velocity field, we treated 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as a free parameter and varied it to find what 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 value appropriately removes the anisotropy in redshift-space.
 he motivation behind the project is that LPT can model the non-linear density
 field on smaller scales compared to Eulerian perturbation theory (EPT)
 (
\color red
citation
\color inherit
).
 So, using LPT gives us the advantage that the method is possible valid
 on smaller scales and can utilize mode number of modes to measure 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin this section with a derivation of Kaiser approximation and an algorithm
 for reconstruction of RSD in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Background"

\end_inset

.
 Following that, we show how the reconstruction method recovers velocity
 fields/real-space density field from the redshift-space density field in
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Reconstructing_field"

\end_inset

 and describe how this method enables us to measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 for the case of DM particles and DM halos in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:measure_f"

\end_inset

.
 In Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:discussion_rsd"

\end_inset

, we discuss the implication of these results for measurements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and reconstruction of real-space density.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Background 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Background"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we present the Kaiser approximation, the relation between
 EPT and LPT, and the algorithm to reconstruct the real-space density field
 from the redshift-space density field.
 We begin Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:kaiser"

\end_inset

 by deriving the Kaiser approximation in EPT.
 In Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:LPT"

\end_inset

, we demonstrate why the first-order LPT can model smaller scales than the
 first-order EPT.
 In Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Algorithm"

\end_inset

, we outline the reconstruction algorithm and show how to measure the growth
 rate 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 through the reconstruction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Kaiser Approximation 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:kaiser"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Kaiser approximation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1987MNRAS.227....1K"

\end_inset

 models the redshift-space distortions in linear regimes and provides a
 way to measure the growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $f\approx\Omega_{m}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 to constrain 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{m}$
\end_inset

 as well as to test GR/modified gravity.
 In this section, we derive the Kaiser approximation and compare its prediction
 to non-linear power spectra.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When positions of galaxies are measured through redshift, the measured positions
 are slightly shifted from their actual positions due to the peculiar velocities
 of galaxies such as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{s}\equiv\vec{r}+\frac{v_{z}}{H_{o}}\hat{z},\label{eq:redshift space position-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{r}$
\end_inset

 is the position in real-space, 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{z}$
\end_inset

 is the line-of-sight component of the particle velocity and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{o}$
\end_inset

 is the Hubble constant.
 Here, we use the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

plane-parallel
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 approximation, in which the line-of-sight directions for all particles
 are assumed to be the z-axis (i.e., assuming that an observer is at infinity).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conservation of mass provides 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\vec{s})d^{3}s=\rho_{r}(\vec{r})d^{3}r$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{r}$
\end_inset

 are the densities in redshift-space and real-space.
 Then, we can expand the terms in the following way.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\rho_{s}(\vec{s}) & = & \rho_{r}(\vec{r})\left|\frac{d^{3}r}{d^{3}s}\right|\\
 & = & \rho_{r}(\vec{r})(1+\frac{u_{z}}{z})^{-2}(1+\frac{du_{z}}{dz})^{-1}\\
 & \simeq & \rho_{r}(\vec{r})(1-\frac{du_{z}}{dz})
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that going from the second to the last step is a valid approximation
 in the limit that 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{z}/z$
\end_inset

 is small, which holds in linear approximation.
 Now, take Fourier transformation of the last equation.
 The last term of the above equation becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{du_{z}}{dz}\right)_{fourier}=\mu^{2}\theta(k)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(k)\equiv(\nabla\cdot\vec{u})_{fourier}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\equiv k_{z}/k$
\end_inset

.
 In order to obtain the above relation, we assume no vorticity (i.e, the
 velocity field is irrotational) to write 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{z}=-\frac{\partial}{\partial z}\nabla^{-2}\theta$
\end_inset

, which gives 
\begin_inset Formula $(\frac{\partial}{\partial z})^{2}\nabla^{-2})_{fourier}=(k_{z}/k)^{2}=\mu^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, the first order terms for the density field in redshift-space are
 described in terms of the density field in real-space 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}$
\end_inset

 and the velocity divergence 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 such as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{s}(\vec{k})=\delta_{r}(\vec{k})-\mu^{2}\theta(\vec{k}).\label{eq:Kaiser_den}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In linear perturbation theory, we can relate a density field and a velocity
 field such as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\theta(\vec{k})=-f\delta_{matter}(\vec{k})\label{eq:vel-den}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $f\equiv d{\rm ln}D/d{\rm ln}a\approx\Omega_{m}^{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 (Peebles 1980).
 Therefore, in the linear regime, we can relate redshift-space and real-space
 such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{s}(\vec{k})=(1+f\mu^{2})\delta_{r}(\vec{k}).\label{eq:redshift-real}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The power spectrum in redshift-space can be related to the power spectrum
 in real-space through the growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 such as 
\color black

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{s}(\vec{k})\equiv<\delta_{s}^{*}\delta_{s}>=(1+\mu^{2}f)^{2}P_{r}(k),\label{eq:Kaiser_power}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the relationship between redshift-space and real-space power spectra
 is derived from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:redshift-real"

\end_inset

.
 Note that the Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Kaiser_power"

\end_inset

 is valid for matter power spectra.
 Since a redshift-space density field has an angular dependence, we can
 expand the power spectrum by convolving with Legendre polynomials, 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{l}(\mu)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{s}(k,\mu)=\underset{l}{\sum}P^{(l)}(k)L_{l}(\mu),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{s}^{(l)}(k)\equiv\frac{2l+1}{2}\int_{-1}^{+1}P_{s}(k,\mu)L_{l}(\mu)d\mu.
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to measure 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 through the Kaiser approximation, we first take a ratio of quadrupole and
 monopole moments of a redshift-space power spectrum:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P_{s}^{(2)}/P_{s}^{(0)}=(\frac{4}{3}f+\frac{4}{7}f^{2})/(1+\frac{2}{3}f+\frac{1}{5}f^{2}),\label{eq:kaiser_ratio}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and measure the ratio to obtain the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Kaiser"

\end_inset

 shows the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}^{(2)}/P_{s}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

 for the DM particles at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

.
 The detail of the samples used to compute the power spectra is in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Reconstructing_field"

\end_inset

.
 The result tells us that the Kaiser approximation is valid only on 
\begin_inset Formula $k<0.02h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

.
 From Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Kaiser"

\end_inset

, measured 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

s are 
\begin_inset Formula $f=0.417$
\end_inset

 with the error of the mean of 0.01 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f=0.765$
\end_inset

 with the error of the mean of 0.01 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

.
 In order to measure the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, we used the ratios on the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in[0.01,0.02][h{\rm Mpc^{-1}]}$
\end_inset

.
 Both measured 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 values are underestimated compared to expected 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 values from the cosmology used in the simulations, which are 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

=0.466 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

=0.84 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 The main cause of this underestimation is due to the fact that the ratio
 of non-linear matter power spectrum already deviates from the Kaiser approximat
ion at 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0.02h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_RSD/Kaiser_dm.pdf
	width 60col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The ratio of monopole and quadrupole moments of redshift-space matter power
 spectrum at z=0.0 and z=1.0.
 Solid lines represent the ratio of non-linear matter power spectra and
 the corresponding dashed lines show their predicted values using the Kaiser
 approximation.
 Error bars are the error of the mean over ten simulations.
 The Kaiser approximation is valid only on 
\begin_inset Formula $k<0.02h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Kaiser"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, we repeat the same exercise for DM halos whose masses are greater than
 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 DM halos and galaxies are biased tracer of DM particles, which means that
 the density for those biased tracers are defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{halo/gal}=b\delta_{DM}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a bias parameter.
 On large scales, this bias parameter is scale-independent and therefore
 can be treated as the constant parameter.
 Measuring the Kaiser approximation through such biased tracers, the ratio
 in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:kaiser_ratio"

\end_inset

 becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{s}^{(2)}/P_{s}^{(0)}=(\frac{4}{3}\beta+\frac{4}{7}\beta^{2})/(1+\frac{2}{3}\beta+\frac{1}{5}\beta^{2})
\]

\end_inset

where we define 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=f/b$
\end_inset

.
 This comes from 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{s}^{(hao/gal)}(\vec{k})=(b+f\mu^{2})\delta_{r}^{(DM)}(\vec{k})=b(1+\frac{f}{b}\mu^{2})\delta_{r}^{(DM)}=(1+\beta\mu^{2})\delta_{r}^{(halo/gal)}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the bias parameter is scale-dependent on small scales, and therefore
 it adds one more complication in the measurement of the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and constraining GR/modified gravity, which often uses the scale-dependence
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Kaiser-halo"

\end_inset

 shows the ratio 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{s}^{(2)}/P_{s}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

 of DM halos whose masses are greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

.
 The wiggle appearing in those ratios on a very sma
\color black
ll 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is due to the limited size of the simulation box.
 Because of that, measured 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 values are sensitive to the change of the range in 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $k<k_{{\rm max}}\approx0.05h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

, measured 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 values are 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 = 0.316 with the error of the mean of 0.02 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 and 0.285 with the error of the mean of 0.02 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_RSD/Kaiser_halo13.0.pdf
	lyxscale 60
	width 60col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
