 spectrum for DM halos at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

.
 Solid lines represent the ratio of non-linear matter power spectra and
 the corresponding dashed lines show their predicted values using the Kaiser
 approximation.
 Error bars are calculated from the error of the mean over ten simulations.
 Here we only used halos whose mass is above 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 The Kaiser approximation is valid only on 
\begin_inset Formula $k<0.05h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
EPT/LPT: The Kaiser Approximation in LPT
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:LPT"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In LPT, the Eulerian position of a mass element, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{r}$
\end_inset

, is related to its initial Lagrangian position, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{q}$
\end_inset

, through a displacement vector field,
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Psi}(\vec{q})$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\vec{r}=\vec{q}+\vec{\Psi}(\vec{q}).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By using the above definition, real-space overdensity in configuration-space
 and fourier-space are defined as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{r}(\vec{r})=\int d^{3}\vec{q}\{\delta^{(D)}(\vec{r}-\vec{q}-\vec{\Psi}(\vec{q}))-1\},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{(D)}$
\end_inset

 is the 3D Dirac delta function and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}\equiv(\rho_{r}-\bar{\rho})/\bar{\rho}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{r}$
\end_inset

 is real-space density and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\rho}$
\end_inset

 is mean density, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{r}(\vec{k})=\int d^{3}\vec{q}e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}(e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi}}-1).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Note that this integration over 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{q}$
\end_inset

 is equivalent to summing all the particles whose initial coordinates are
 denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{q}_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,...,N$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is the total number of particles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the above description, redshift-space density (
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{s}\equiv\vec{r}+\frac{v_{z}}{H_{0}}\hat{z}$
\end_inset

) is described as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{s}(\vec{s})=\int d^{3}\vec{q}\{\delta^{(D)}(\vec{s}-\vec{q}-\vec{\Psi}_{s}(\vec{q}))-1\},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Psi}_{s}\equiv\vec{\Psi}+v_{z}/H_{0}\hat{z}$
\end_inset

, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{s}(\vec{k})=\int d^{3}\vec{q}e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}(e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi}_{s}}-1)=\int d^{3}\vec{q}e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}(e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot(\vec{\Psi}+v_{z}/H_{0}\hat{z})}-1).\label{eq:redshift_in_fourier}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By expanding the term 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-ik_{z}v_{z}}$
\end_inset

 in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:redshift_in_fourier"

\end_inset

 as a Taylor series, we obtain
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\delta_{s}(\vec{k}) & = & \int d^{3}\vec{q}e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}\{e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi}}(1-ik_{z}v_{z}/H_{0}+\cdots)-1\}\\
 & = & \int d^{3}\vec{q}e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}(e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi}}-1)+\int d^{3}\vec{q}e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi}}(-ik_{z}v_{z}/H_{0})+\cdots\\
 & \approx & \delta_{r}(\vec{k})+\int d^{3}\vec{r}e^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{r}}(-ik_{z}v_{z}/H_{0})\\
 & = & \delta_{r}(\vec{k})+\mu^{2}\theta(\vec{k}),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which is the same as Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Kaiser_den"

\end_inset

.
 In the perturbation theorem, we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\delta\right|\ll1$
\end_inset

 and therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|v_{z}\right|\ll1$
\end_inset

.
 By taking the first-order term of 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-ik_{z}v_{z}}$
\end_inset

 , we obtain the Kaiser approximation (i.e., the first order EPT).
 The reason the first-order LPT works better than EPT is because LPT naturally
 takes care of higher-order terms, which is consistent with the fact that
 the Zeldovich approximation works better than the first-order EPT (e.g.,
 
\color red
XXX
\color inherit
).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\size normal
Algorithm
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Algorithm"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we present the algorithm to reconstruct the real-space
 density field from redshift-space through shifting the particle positions
 back by the distance due to their velocities.
 This reconstruction naturally provides a description in terms of LPT.
 The motivation behind of this method is that LPT takes care of higher-order
 terms as shown in the previous section, and therefore the reconstruction
 can remove anisotropy in redshift-space beyond the regime the Kaiser approximat
ion is valid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to reconstruct real-space density, we need to remove anisotropy
 generated by LOS components of peculiar velocities.
 So, the crucial step in our reconstruction method is that particles in
 redshift-space are shifted back by their peculiar velocities calculated
 from linear perturbation theory.
 The procedure for this calculation is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Take a redshift-space density field and divide it by 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+f\mu^{2})$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1987MNRAS.227....1K"

\end_inset

) to obtain real-space density approximated from linear perturbation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}(\vec{k})=\frac{\delta_{s}}{1+f\mu^{2}}.\label{eq:Kaiser2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Smooth 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{Kaiser}$
\end_inset

 to filter out high 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 modes with a Gaussian smoothing of scale 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S(k)$
\end_inset

, to eliminate the effect of small-scale, non-linear structure of the density
 field:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S(k)={\rm e}^{-(kR)^{2}/2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compute the velocity field from linear perturbation theory:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla\cdot\vec{v}_{{\rm lin}}=-f\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}(\vec{x)}\Longleftrightarrow\vec{v}_{{\rm lin}}(\vec{k})=\frac{i\vec{k}f}{k^{2}}\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}(\vec{k}).\label{eq:linear_velocity}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Shift the particles in redshift-space by 
\begin_inset Formula $-\vec{v}_{{\rm lin}}/H_{0}$
\end_inset

 and compute the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reconstructed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 density field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm recon}}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{{\rm recon}}(\vec{k})=\int d^{3}q{\rm e}^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}({\rm e}^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi s}(\vec{q})+ik_{z}v_{z,{\rm lin}}/H_{o}}-1)\label{eq:recon_LPT1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{\Psi}_{s}(\vec{q})=\vec{\Psi}(\vec{q})+\frac{v_{z,{\rm NL}}}{H_{o}}\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 from Eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:redshift_in_fourier"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that we take advantage of periodicity of the simulations to perform
 all of these steps using fast Fourier transforms.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\color black
For the non-periodic case, see Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2012arXiv1202.0090P"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We define the density field through the CIC assignment 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1981csup.book.....H"

\end_inset

 and allocate the linear velocities to particles through the inverse CIC
 assignment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to measure 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, we treat 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as a free parameter.
 Since there is no anisotropy in real-space, the quadrupole moment of the
 power spectrum in real-space must be zero.
 Using the quadrupole moments measure the residual anisotropy, we test what
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 properly removes the anisotropy from the redshift-space density field.
 
\color black
The assumption here is that the 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 value which removes anisotropy is the 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 value from the cosmology measured.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that we are not exactly computing linear velocity, because we use the
 non-linear density field smoothed by the Gaussian filter as well as the
 redshift-space density field divided by the Kaiser approximation (hereafter,
 the Kaiser density) as shown in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Kaiser2"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We described the reconstructed density in terms of LPT (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:recon_LPT1"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\delta_{{\rm recon}}(\vec{k})=\int d^{3}q{\rm e}^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}\{\exp(-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi}(\vec{q})+ik_{z}v_{z,{\rm NL}}/H_{0}+ik_{z}v_{z,{\rm lin}}/H_{0})-1\},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{z,{\rm NL}}$
\end_inset

 is a velocity of particles and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{z,{\rm lin}}$
\end_inset

 is the linear velocity estimated from the Kaiser density.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{z,{\rm NL}}=v_{z,{\rm lin}}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm recon}}(\vec{k})=\delta_{r}(\vec{k})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On very large scales where the Kaiser approximation is valid, the reconstructed
 density can be approximated as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\delta_{{\rm recon}} & = & \int d^{3}\vec{q}{\rm e}^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}\{\exp(-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi}-ik_{z}v_{z,{\rm NL}}/H_{0}+ik_{z}v_{z,{\rm lin}}/H_{0})-1\}\\
 & = & \int d^{3}\vec{q}{\rm e}^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}}\{\exp(-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi})-1\}+\int d^{3}\vec{q}{\rm e}^{-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{q}-i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{\Psi}}(-ik_{z}v_{z,{\rm NL}}/H_{0}+ik_{z}v_{z,{\rm lin}}/H_{0})+\cdots\\
 & \approx & \delta_{r}(\vec{k})+\mu^{2}\theta_{{\rm NL}}(\vec{k})-\mu^{2}\theta_{{\rm lin}}(\vec{k}).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{{\rm NL}}\approx\theta_{{\rm lin}}$
\end_inset

, then we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm recon}}\approx\delta_{r}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Reconstructing the Real-Space Density Fields
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Reconstructing_field"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we examine how well the reconstruction technique can recover
 the velocity fields and the real-space density fields as well as aggregate
 statistics such as power spectra.
 We run a set of comparisons with the 10 boxes each with 10732952 particles
 in a cubical box whose side length is 2000 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 All of the simulations are randomly selected subsamples of a full simulation
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $1024^{3}$
\end_inset

 particles.
 The simulations assume a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

CDM cosmology with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{m,0}=0.25$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\Lambda,0}=0.75$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

=0.55.
 The non-linear velocity fields and the real-space density fields from the
 simulations are the baseline against to the velocity/density fields reconstruct
ed from the redshift-space density fields.
 Note that we use the growth rate 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 computed from the cosmology used in the simulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Estimating velocity fields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we present how well linear perturbation theory can estimate
 the velocity fields.
 To do that, we first compute velocity fields using the volume-weighted
 method, which defines velocities by dividing momentum by mass on each grid.
 Note that the volume-weighted velocities are sensitive to grid sizes, because
 large number of grids make a majority of grids empty and therefore the
 velocities on those grids are zero even though the velocity field is not.
 To avoid having ill-defined velocities, we used 
\begin_inset Formula $128^{3}$
\end_inset

 grids here.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we estimate linear velocities using the density fields from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linear_velocity"

\end_inset

.
 Here, we decide to use two different density fields -- the real-space density
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}$
\end_inset

 and the Kaiser density 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}$
\end_inset

 defined as Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Kaiser2"

\end_inset

.
 The reason we use those two density fields to compute linear velocities
 is because we cannot observe the real-space density field and need to use
 the Kaiser density in actual observations, but we also want to know how
 the estimated velocity fields differ by using those different density fields.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:vel_diff"

\end_inset

 compares the LOS velocities 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{z}$
\end_inset

 linearly estimated from 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}$
\end_inset

 to the non-linear velocities 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{{\rm NL}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 The linear velocities are reassigned to DM particles through the inverse
 CIC assignment after the velocity fields are computed.
 The figure shows that using 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}$
\end_inset

 make little difference in the estimation of linear velocities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_RSD/histogram_lin_veldiff_sm0_z0.pdf
	lyxscale 50
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\color black
\begin_inset CommandInset label
