\begin_inset Formula $v_{z}$
\end_inset

 of DM particles at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 We compute the linear velocities using the real-space density 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}$
\end_inset

 and the Kaiser density 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}$
\end_inset

.
 The difference between the linear velocities estimated from two different
 density fields is XXX.
 Note that the linear velocities are reassigned to particles through the
 inverse CIC assignment with smoothing of 10
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reconstructed density field
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We next test how well the reconstruction method can recover the real-space
 density field with the correct value for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 We first compute the reconstructed density field from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:recon_LPT1"

\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Scatter-dm-z0"

\end_inset

 compares the redshift-space and reconstructed density fields, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm recon}}$
\end_inset

, to the real-space density field 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 using 
\begin_inset Formula $128^{3}$
\end_inset

 grids.
 The scatter between 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm recon}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}$
\end_inset

 is reduced to 
\begin_inset Formula $26.9\%$
\end_inset

 compared to the scatter between 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}$
\end_inset

 as shown in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:dm_den_grid128"

\end_inset

.
 (
\color red
talk about the slope...
\color inherit
) We also compared the scatter between 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}$
\end_inset

 in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:dm_den_grid128"

\end_inset

.
 Even for the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}$
\end_inset

, the scatter is reduced to 
\begin_inset Formula $69.2\%$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

