\begin_layout Subsection
Power spectra with reconstruction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By comparing the velocity/density fields in the previous sections, we show
 that the reconstruction method can recover the real-space density field
 better than the Kaiser approximation.
 Now, we present at what scales the power spectrum computed from the reconstruct
ed density field agrees with the power spectrum in real space.
 To this end, we applied the reconstruction method to the redshift-space
 density field and then computed the power spectrum.
 
\color black
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:recon-mono"

\end_inset

 compares the reconstructed power spectrum and the Kaiser approximation,
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{{\rm Kaiser}}=(1+\frac{2}{3}f+\frac{1}{5}f^{2})P_{r}$
\end_inset

, to the real/redshift-space power spectra at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 While the Kaiser approximation agrees with the power spectrum in redshift-space
 up to 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{{\rm max}}\sim0.05h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

, the reconstructed power spectrum agrees with the real-space power spectrum
 up to 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{{\rm max}}\sim0.1h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Cross-dm"

\end_inset

 shows cross correlation coefficients of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm recon}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{r}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 We computed the cross correlation coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 using the power spectra such that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
r=\frac{<\delta_{{\rm recon}}^{*}\delta_{r}>}{<\delta_{{\rm recon}}^{*}\delta_{{\rm recon}}><\delta_{r}^{*}\delta_{r}>}=\frac{P_{{\rm recon},r}^{(cross)}}{P_{{\rm recon}}^{(auto)}P_{r}^{(auto)}},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{(auto)}$
\end_inset

 is an auto power spectrum and 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{(cross)}$
\end_inset

 is a cross power spectrum.
 Having 1 for cross correlation coefficients means that those two density
 fields are perfectly correlated each other.
 The cross correlation coefficient for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm recon}}$
\end_inset

 is closer to 1 on smaller scale than that for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm Kaiser}}$
\end_inset

, which is consistent with Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:recon-mono"

\end_inset

.
 Together with our data from Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:recon-mono"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Cross-dm"

\end_inset

 indicate that our reconstruction with the proper 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 value can recover real-space density at the scale that the Kaiser approximation
 breaks down.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_RSD/recon_dm_real.pdf
	lyxscale 90
	width 60col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\color black
Solid lines represent real-space density power spectrum (blue) and redshift-spac
e power spectrum (green) at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 Blue circles represent the reconstructed power spectrum and green circles
 are the monopole term of the Kaiser approximation.
 Here we used 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 = 0.466.
 The reconstructed density power spectrum with the expected 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 recovers real-space matter power spectrum up to 
\begin_inset Formula $k\sim0.1h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

, while the Kaiser approximation deviates from the redshift-space power
 spectrum on larger scales.
 Error bars are calculated from the error of the mean over ten simulations.
\color inherit

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:recon-mono"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

