\begin_layout Section
Measuring the growth rate through reconstruction 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:measure_f"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Reconstructing_field"

\end_inset

, we demonstrate that reconstruction can recover real-space density from
 redshift-space on large scales.
 In this section, we treat 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as a free parameter and demonstrate the accuracy with which we can measure
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 value through reconstruction.
 We hypothesize that the proper 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 value will permit our reconstruction to successfully remove all of the
 anisotropy from redshift-space.
 In order to identify the proper 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 value, we assess residual anisotropy by calculating the quadrupole moment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the following, we demonstrate the measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $f/\beta$
\end_inset

 value through reconstruction for DM particles and DM halos.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
DM particles 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:recon_dm"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the algorithm described in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Algorithm"

\end_inset

, we first reconstruct the density field with various values of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Then, we computed the quadrupole moments from those reconstructed density
 fields.
 Here, we want to find the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, which removes anisotropy on large scales.
 In order to find such a value, we calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 of those quadrupole moments with respect to zero:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi^{2}=\sum_{j=1}^{M}\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{N}(P_{{\rm recon,i}}^{(2)}(k_{j}))^{2}}{\sigma(k_{j})^{2}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}\equiv\sum_{i=1}^{N}\{(P_{{\rm recon,i}}^{(2)})^{2}/N-(\bar{P}_{{\rm recon}}^{(2)})^{2}\}$
\end_inset

.
 This will allow us to find the correct 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 value, which makes the quadrupole moment zero.
 The underlying assumption is that if a chosen 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 value does not properly recover real-space density through reconstruction,
 there must be some residual anisotropy from redshift-space density and
 quadrupole moments evaluate this residual anisotropy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We computed the quadrupole moments for the reconstructed density fields
 with various values of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and their corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 values at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:recon-ratio-quad-1"

\end_inset

 .
 The smoothing scales used here is 
\begin_inset Formula $10h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

.
 In the left panel of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:recon-ratio-quad-1"

\end_inset

 , the solid lines are the quadrupole moments for 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{{\rm recon}}$
\end_inset

 with various 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 value corresponding to the cosmology used for the simulation is shown as
 the red solid line, while the quadrupole moment of the real-space density
 field is shown as a red dashed line.
 This figure tells us two things.
 One is that the reconstruction method removes anisotropy up to 
\begin_inset Formula $k<0.05h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

 which is better than the Kaiser approximation.
 The other thing is that the proper 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 value overestimates the velocity field and therefore over-removes the anisotrop
y.
 This is consistent with the right panel of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:recon-ratio-quad-1"

\end_inset

 , which shows the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 values for various 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 The corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 value for the minimum 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $f=0.455$
\end_inset

.
 This yields a 
\begin_inset Formula $1.1\%$
\end_inset

 measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, but with a residual bias of 
\begin_inset Formula $2.4\%$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement t
wide true
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_RSD/Recon_dm_quadr_z0.0.pdf
	width 60text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/old_ts485/Desktop/my_thesis/plots_RSD/Chisq_Az9_dm_z0_kcut0.05.pdf
	width 60text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Left: Quadrupole moments of the reconstructed-density power spectra divided
 by a real-space matter power spectrum at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 The dotted line is the real-space quadrupole moment.
 Solid lines show the reconstructed densities with 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 as shown in the legend.
 The reconstructed power spectrum with correct 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 agrees with the real-space power spectrum up to 
\begin_inset Formula $k<0.05[h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}]$
\end_inset

, which is beyond the scale that the Kaiser approximation is valid.
 Here, we use smoothing scale of 10
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 Error bars are calculated from the error of the mean over ten simulations.
 
\color red
Right: 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 of the reconstructed quadrupole moments with respect to zero, as a function
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 are minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0.455$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 has 5 degrees of freedom.

\color inherit
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:recon-ratio-quad-1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In light of our findings that the reconstructed quadrupoles largely deviate
 from the real-space quadrupole moment on small scales, we wondered whether
 this is due to failing to model the FoG effect or due to a choice of smoothing
 scales.
 We therefore apply the reconstruction method with various smoothing scales
 and the fixed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, and compute the quadrupole moments as shown in Figure 
\color black

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:power-smoothing1"

\end_inset

 .
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:power-smoothing1"

\end_inset

 tells us that the reconstruction method is sensitive to the choice of smoothing
 scales.
 For the case of the smoothing scale of 
\begin_inset Formula $20h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

, the effect of RSDs on small scales remain and the anisotropy is not completely
 removed even on large scales.
 This is because large smoothing scales kill the high-
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 modes and therefore cannot model small scale velocities.
 On the other hand, for the case of smoothing scales of 
\begin_inset Formula $5h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

, the velocities are over-estimated on all scales and the quadrupole moment
 goes to negative; however, the amplitude is almost flat up to 
\begin_inset Formula $k<0.1h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that using the smoothing scale of 
\begin_inset Formula $5h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 will introduce larger bias on the measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, but we can use more modes (i.e., going to smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

) in the measurement.
 Due to the sensitivity of the reconstruction on smoothing scales, we conclude
 that the deviation of the reconstructed quadrupoles on small scales is
 mainly due to the choice of smoothing scales.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_RSD/Recon_dm_sm_quadr_z0.0.pdf
	lyxscale 60
	width 60col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Quadrupole moments of the reconstructed power spectra with various smoothing
 scales with fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $f=0.466$
\end_inset

.
 Without smoothing, the quadrupole moment becomes smaller than zero for
 all scales due to a slight overestimation of velocity on a small scale
 (See Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:histogram_vel_dm"

\end_inset

), while large smoothing scales do not recover real-space.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:power-smoothing1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
DM Halos
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now consider possible observational consequences of the reconstruction
 method by applying to DM halos.

\color black
 Rather than attempting to reconstruct galaxy models, we concentrate on
 mass limited samples of halos.
 Note that none of the crucial aspects are lost with this simplification.
 We used 10 simulations with XXX particles in a box with 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{box}=1500h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 
\color inherit
The simulations for DM halos are of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda CDM$
\end_inset

 cosmology with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{m}=0.23$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\Lambda}=0.77$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0.55$
\end_inset

.
 Halos are identified by using the Friend-of-Friend algorithm
\color black
 with a linking length of XXX.
 The samples only contain halos with mass greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color black
We go through the same procedure as in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:recon_dm"

\end_inset

.
 The only difference is that now we measure the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 In order to estimate the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, we first measure halo bias taking the ratio between halo and matter power
 spectra such as
\color inherit
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b_{halo}\equiv\sqrt{P_{halo}/P_{DM}}.\label{eq:bias}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\color black
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:halo-bias"

\end_inset

 shows the halo bias measured by taking the ratio with the real-space halo
 power spectrum as well as the reconstructed halo power spectrum.
 The reason we also show the result using the reconstructed power spectrum
 is because we cannot use the real-space power spectrum in real observations.
 People often use the angular correlation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{p}(r_{p})$
\end_inset

 to measure the bias; however, the angular correlation function introduces
 a systematic bias in the measurement (
\color red
cite: white et al.
\color black
).
 The figure tells us that we can measure the bias using the reconstructed
 power spectrum.

\color inherit
 Quantitatively, the biases measured through the real-space power spectrum
 are 1.53 (with the error of the mean of 0.02) and 3.18 (with the error of
 0.04) at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 For reconstructed densities, we use a best fit 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 value which have the minimum 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 values as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Chisq-halo"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_RSD/halo13.0_bias_z0.pdf
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Ratio of halo and DM power spectra, which is proportional to square of the
 scale-dependent halo bias 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{halo}$
\end_inset

.
 Blue line represents the ratio of real-space densities and green line is
 reconstructed densities at z=0.0.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:halo-bias"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the halo bias is 
\begin_inset Formula $1.53$
\end_inset

, the expected value for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $0.291$
\end_inset


\color black
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, the expected value at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=0.222$
\end_inset

.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Chisq-halo"

\end_inset

 shows the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 values measured through the quadrupole moments as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\color inherit
We use 
\begin_inset Formula $10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 as a smoothing scale for the reconstruction method.
 Through the 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 analysis, the best fit 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

s are 
\begin_inset Formula $0.32$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0.255$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 Those values are larger than the expected values, which is an opposite
 trend compared to the case of DM particles (
\color red
want to re-do the analysis
\color inherit
).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:recon-ratio-halo"

\end_inset

 shows monopole and quadrupole moments of reconstructed density with the
 best fit 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 values at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

.
 We successfully recovers the real-space power spectrum up to 
\begin_inset Formula $k<0.04h{\rm Mpc}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, but the amplitude of the monopole terms is slightly smaller than the one
 for the real-space power spectrum.
\end_layout

