\begin_layout Section

\size normal
Discussion/Summary 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:discussion_rsd"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study, we measure the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 using the reconstruction method, which naturally provides a description
 in terms of LPT.
 The motivation behind this study is that LPT can model the non-linearity
 of the density field on smaller scales that EPT (i.e., the reconstruction
 method enables us to use more modes in 
\begin_inset Formula $P(k)$
\end_inset

 to measure the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method, however, underestimates the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 for the case of DM particles, which yields a 
\begin_inset Formula $1.1\%$
\end_inset

 measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, but with a residual bias of 
\begin_inset Formula $2.4\%$
\end_inset

.
 For the case of DM halos, the method overestimates the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 with a residual bias of 
\begin_inset Formula $10.0\%$
\end_inset

.
 This may be because we use the non-linear density field to estimate the
 linear velocity fields, but we are uncertain about the cause.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There have been several studies trying to reconstruct velocity fields from
 the density field beyond linear perturbation theories.
 Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kitaura_2012"

\end_inset

 shows that using the tidal tensors successfully recovers velocity fields
 on scales greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $5h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 Although using higher-order terms require more number of free parameters
 (unless assuming certain cosmologies), this may be a way to correct the
 residual bias in the measurement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We conclude the chapter with an over view of our primary results:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(1) Our reconstruction method recovers real-space density fields from redshift-s
pace up to 
\begin_inset Formula $k\sim0.05h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(2) The measurement yields a 
\begin_inset Formula $1.1\%$
\end_inset

 measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, but with a residual bias of 
\begin_inset Formula $2.4\%$
\end_inset

 for the case of DM particles.
 For the case of DM halos, the residual bias for the measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $10.0\%$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(3) The method is sensitive to the choice of smoothing scales.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Scale-Dependence of Halo Assembly Bias
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two-point clustering of dark matter halos is influenced by halo properties
 besides mass, a phenomenon referred to as 
\shape italic
halo assembly bias
\shape default
.
 Using the depth of the gravitational potential well, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

, as our secondary halo property, in this paper we present the first study
 of the scale-dependence of assembly bias.
 In the large-scale linear regime, 
\begin_inset Formula $r\geq10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc},$
\end_inset

 our findings are in keeping with previous results.
 In particular, at the low-mass end (
\begin_inset Formula $<\mcoll\approx10^{12.5}\msun$
\end_inset

), halos with high-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 show stronger large-scale clustering relative to halos with low-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 of the same mass; this trend weakens and reverses for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir\gtrsim\mcoll.$
\end_inset

 In the nonlinear regime, assembly bias in low-mass halos exhibits a pronounced
 scale-dependent 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bump
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $500\kpch-5\mpch$
\end_inset

.
 This feature weakens and eventually vanishes for halos of higher mass.
 We show that this scale-dependent signature can primarily be attributed
 to a special subpopulation of
\shape italic
 ejected halos
\shape default
, defined as present-day host halos that were previously members of a higher-mas
s halo at some point in their past history.
 A corollary of our results is that galaxy clustering on scales of 
\begin_inset Formula $r\sim1-2\mpch$
\end_inset

 can be impacted by up to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim15\%$
\end_inset

 by the choice of the halo property used in the halo model, even for stellar
 mass-limited samples.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The halo model provides a connection between dark matter halos and galaxies,
 and it has been remarkably successful in describing observations of galaxy
 clustering (for a recent review, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "seljak00,vdboschBOOK"

\end_inset

).
 In particular, the Halo Occupation Distribution (HOD) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "berlind02,berlind03"

\end_inset

 and the Conditional Luminosity Function (CLF) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "yang03"

\end_inset

 are the two most widely used models of the galaxy-halo connection.
 These models start from the assumption that halo mass completely determines
 the galaxy occupation statistics.
 In order to populate halos with galaxies, the HOD specifies the probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $P(N|M)$
\end_inset

 that a halo with mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 hosts 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 galaxies, while the CLF models the mean abundance 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi(L|M)$
\end_inset

 of galaxies with luminosity 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 in halos of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 These two models are interchangeable; integrating the CLF over luminosity
 yields an HOD.
 Both models have been applied extensively to observations in order to study
 the galaxy-halo connection 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "magliocchetti03,zehavi05a,yang_etal05,zheng07,vdBosch07,zheng09,skibba09,simon_etal09,ross10,zehavi11,leauthaud11b,leauthaud12,geach12,parejko13"

\end_inset

 as well as cosmology 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "tinker05,more_etal13,cacciato_etal13,mandelbaum13"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the clustering of halos also exhibits a dependence on additional
 properties beyond their mass 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gao_etal05,wechsler06,gao_white07,li_etal08,hahn_etal09"

\end_inset

, a phenomenon generically referred to as 
\shape italic
halo assembly bias
\shape default
.
 This can be traced back to the fact that halos of the same mass in different
 environments have different assembly histories and cluster differently.
 Having different assembly histories also affects the internal structure
 of halos 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bullock01,wechsler02,hahn_etal07b,faltenbacher_white10"

\end_inset

.
 This, in turn, results in a clustering dependence on the structural properties
 of a halo, including the depth of its gravitational potential well, characteriz
ed by its maximum circular velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

.
 The present work revisits this manifestation of halo assembly bias, and
 extends it down to smaller scales (
\begin_inset Formula $<10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

) than has been previously explored.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative approach to connecting halos and galaxies is abundance matching
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kravtsov04a,vale_ostriker04,vale_ostriker06,tasitsiomi_etal04,conroy_wechsler09,guo10,simha10,neistein11a,watson_etal12b,rod_puebla12,hearin_etal12b,kravtsov13,saito15"

\end_inset

.
 In its simplest form, abundance matching posits a monotonic relationship
 between a property of a galaxy (luminosity, stellar mass) and that of a
 halo (mass, potential well depth).
 By construction, such a relationship preserves the rank ordering of the
 galaxies and halos.
 The choice of the observationally-relevant halo property is a priori unknown;
 this uncertainty that can lead to significant systematic errors when using
 halo models to interpret galaxy clustering measurements 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "zentner_etal13"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A recent parallel research effort has been revisiting the standard subdivision
 of dark matter halos into host/sub-halos, a classification that naturally
 depends on how the halo boundary is chosen.
 While the virial radius is the most commonly chosen definition, recent
 work has demonstrated that the environmental effects of halos extends well
 beyond the virial radius 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wetzel_etal13,diemer14,adhikari14,wetzel_nagai14,more15"

\end_inset

.
 In particular, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wetzel_etal13"

\end_inset

 argue that these environmental effects are due to ejected subhalos which
 orbit beyond the virial radius of their hosts, and therefore get temporarily
 reclassified as host halos.
 These studies argue that a more physically motivated boundary is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

splashback radius
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 corresponding to the caustic from material just reaching its first apocentric
 passage.
 One of the chief results of the present work is that the halo assembly
 bias on small scales predominantly arises from this mis-classification.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The outline of this paper is as follows.
 Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

2 summarizes the simulations we use in this work.
 Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

3 presents our primary results - characterizing the dependence of the clustering
 of halos on 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

; Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

4 explores some of the implications of these results.
 We conclude in Sec.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

5.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the Bolshoi 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bolshoi_11"

\end_inset

 and MultiDark simulations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "riebe_etal11,prada_etal11"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Flex Flex:URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://www.MultiDark.org
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 in this work; the combination of these simulations allows us to span a
 large range in halo mass.
 We summarize key properties of these simulations here.
 Both simulations were run with the Adaptive Refinement Tree Code 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kravtsov_etal97,gottloeber_klypin08"

\end_inset

 assuming a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda{\rm CDM}$
\end_inset

 model with density parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{m}=0.27$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\Lambda}=0.73$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{b}=0.0469$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{8}=0.82$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0.95$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0.70$
\end_inset

.
 The Bolshoi simulation used 
\begin_inset Formula $2048^{3}$
\end_inset

 particles in a 
\begin_inset Formula $250h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 box with a force resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm kpc}$
\end_inset

, giving a particle mass of 
\begin_inset Formula $1.35\times10^{8}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, while the MultiDark simulation used 
\begin_inset Formula $2048^{3}$
\end_inset

 particles in a 
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm Gpc}$
\end_inset

 box with a force resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $7h^{-1}{\rm kpc}$
\end_inset

 giving a particle mass of 
\begin_inset Formula $8.721\times10^{9}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 Dark matter halos and subhalos are identified using the 
\family typewriter
ROCKSTAR
\family default
 phase-space, temporal halo finder 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rockstar"

\end_inset

 and merger trees are constructed using the 
\family typewriter
CONSISTENT TREES 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rockstar_trees"

\end_inset


\family default
  procedures
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The catalogues used in this paper are publicly available at 
\begin_inset Flex Flex:URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://hipacc.ucsc.edu/Bolshoi/MergerTrees.html
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 All of the results we consider here are at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In what follows, we use the virial masses and maximum circular velocities
 (tagged 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\family typewriter
mvir
\family default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\family typewriter
vmax
\family default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) directly from the halo catalogues.
 The 
\family typewriter
ROCKSTAR
\family default
 halo finder computes halo masses based on spherical overdensities using
 a threshold of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{{\rm h}}=360$
\end_inset

.
 The halo mass and velocity functions start to show incompleteness at 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{10.4}h^{-1}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim200$
\end_inset

 particles) for the Bolshoi simulation, and 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{12}h^{-1}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim100$
\end_inset

 particles) for the MultiDark simulation.
 Below those masses, the halo mass distributions show unphysical drop-offs
 indicating incomplete mass resolution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to the standard classification of halos into host halos (not
 within the virial radius of a more massive halo) and subhalos (within the
 virial radius of a more massive halo), we further classify host halos into
 ejected and non-ejected halos.
 Ejected halos, also referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

backsplash
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 halos, are host halos whose main progenitor was classified, at some point
 in its merger tree history, as a subhalo.
 As we discuss below, these ejected halos have very different clustering
 properties compared to their non-ejected counterparts.
 The ejected fraction for the Bolshoi simulation is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim15.8\%$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{11}h^{-1}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

, and drops to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim6.3\%$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13}h^{-1}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

.
 The lower mass resolution of the MultiDark simulation prevents us from
 making this additional sub-classification.
 Accordingly, results that rely on this split are restricted to the Bolshoi
 simulation and mass range.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Maximum Circular Velocity Dependence of Halo Clustering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we present our primary results.
 We begin in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:samples"

\end_inset

 by describing the sample of halos we use throughout the paper, as well
 as our method for how we categorize halos as having above- or below-average
 circular velocities for their mass.
 In Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:halobias"

\end_inset

, we show the dependence of the clustering of halos on 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Halo Sample Definitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:samples"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the internal structure of a dark matter halo of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir$
\end_inset

 is described by an NFW profile 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "nfw97"

\end_inset

 of concentration 
\begin_inset Formula $c,$
\end_inset

 then its maximum circular velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 is given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overline{V}_{{\rm max}}=0.465M_{{\rm vir}}^{1/3}\sqrt{G(\frac{4}{3}\pi\Delta_{{\rm h}}\rho_{{\rm crit}}\Omega_{m})^{1/3}\frac{c}{{\rm ln(1+c)-c/(1+c)}}}.\label{eq:vmax-mvir}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dutton_maccio14"

\end_inset

, the median concentration-mass relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}(\mvir)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 Bolshoi halos is well-described by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
{\rm log}_{10}\bar{c}=-0.097{\rm log_{10}M_{vir}}+2.148.\label{eq:concen}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

For every halo in the Bolshoi and MultiDark catalogs, we use its tabulated
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir$
\end_inset

 to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}(\mvir),$
\end_inset

 and then use the values 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}$
\end_inset

 together with Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:vmax-mvir"

\end_inset

 to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V}_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 for every halo.
 We will henceforth refer to halos with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax<\meanvmax(\mvir)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

low-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 halos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and halos with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax>\meanvmax(\mvir)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

high-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 halos
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Thus a halo's high- or low-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 designation refers to whether its true 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 value in the simulation is above- or below-average for its mass.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_biasVmax/logVmax_logMvir_Dh360.pdf
	width 60col%

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:vmax-mvir"

\end_inset

Distribution of halo mass and maximum circular velocity at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.0$
\end_inset

 for halos
\color black

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 from the Bolshoi simulation.

\color inherit
 The blue dots represent halos whose observed maximum circular velocity,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,obs}}$
\end_inset

, is greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V}_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

, while the green dots are the ones with smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,obs}}$
\end_inset

 than 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V}_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

.
 The boundary between blue and green dots correspond to 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{V}_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 computed from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:vmax-mvir"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:vmax-mvir"

\end_inset

 illustrates the distribution of Bolshoi halos as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax.$
\end_inset

 High-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 halos are shown in blue, low-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 halos in green.
 The dividing line between the two samples is defined by Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:vmax-mvir"

\end_inset

.
 We find that our analytical approximation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\meanvmax(\mvir)$
\end_inset

 gives a good description of the true median: for any fixed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir,$
\end_inset

 the high-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 and low-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 subsamples have very similar numbers of objects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:vmax-mvir"

\end_inset

 shows a sharp lower bound on the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 at a given 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir,$
\end_inset

 but no sharp upper bound.
 This is ultimately due to the halo mass definition.
 The circular velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm cir}}$
\end_inset

 at the virial radius of any halo is 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm cir}}(\rvir)\equiv V_{{\rm vir}}=\sqrt{G\mvir/\rvir}.$
\end_inset

 Since the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 tabulated in the halo catalog is computed as the maximum value of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm cir}}$
\end_inset

 over the entire profile of the halo, formally 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 cannot exceed 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm vir}}.$
\end_inset

 This manifests as the sharp lower bound seen in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:vmax-mvir"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Halo Bias
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:halobias"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we present our primary results for the clustering properties
 of halos as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax.$
\end_inset

 Clustering strength is quantified by the two-point correlation function,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi(r).$
\end_inset

 In all that follows, we will use 
\begin_inset Formula $\ximm(r)$
\end_inset

 to denote the auto-correlation of the dark matter density field with itself,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xihm(r)$
\end_inset

 to denote the cross-correlation between a sample of halos and the underlying
 density field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Halos are biased tracers of the dark matter density field.
 We denote this bias as 
\begin_inset Formula $\bh,$
\end_inset

 which is in general a function of spatial separation.
 We define halo bias as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bh(r)\equiv\xihm(r)/\ximm(r).
\]

\end_inset

On sufficiently large scales halo bias is approximately linear, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bh(r)$
\end_inset

 approaches a constant value 
\begin_inset Formula $\bhlin.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to measure the bias of a sample of simulated halos for both Bolshoi
 and MultiDark simulations, we estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\ximm(r)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\xihm(r)$
\end_inset

 using a random down-sampling of 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{6}$
\end_inset

 dark matter particles.
 For a given sample of halos, we estimate the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bhlin$
\end_inset

 exhibited by the sample as follows: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
b_{{\rm lin}}=\frac{1}{N_{{\rm bin}}}\sum_{i}(\xi_{{\rm hm}}(r_{i})/\xi_{{\rm mm}}(r_{i})).\label{eq:blindef}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:blindef"

\end_inset

, the sum is performed over 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{{\rm bin}}=20$
\end_inset

 separation bins 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{{\rm i}}$
\end_inset

 linearly spaced from 
\begin_inset Formula $10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $20h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to study the mass-dependence of halo bias, we bin our halos into
 a sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir$
\end_inset

 bins chosen such that there are the same numbers of halos in each bin.
 For MultiDark, we select 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times10^{5}$
\end_inset

 halos for each bin; for Bolshoi we use 
\begin_inset Formula $25000$
\end_inset

 halos per bin.
 The halos in each mass bin are categorized as high-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 or low-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 according to the method described in Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:samples"

\end_inset

.
 We start using halos from the MultiDark simulation for 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}>10^{12.2}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The top panel of Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:linear-bias"

\end_inset

 shows 
\begin_inset Formula $\bhlin$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir;$
\end_inset

 results for high-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 halos are shown in blue, low-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 halos in green.
 At the low-mass end, linear bias is a weak function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir;$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}\gtrsim\mcoll\approx10^{12.8}\msun,$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mcoll$
\end_inset

 is a characteristic mass scale for clustering corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(\mcoll,z)=\delta_{c}\approx1.69$
\end_inset

, we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bhlin$
\end_inset

 increases sharply with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir.$
\end_inset

 Thus the basic shape of each curve in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:linear-bias"

\end_inset

 is in accord with theoretical expectations from the peak-background split
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "sheth_tormen99"

\end_inset

 formalism and Press-Schechter theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pressschechter74"

\end_inset

.
 By comparing the blue and green curves in Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:linear-bias"

\end_inset

 we can see that linear bias has significant dependence upon 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 for halos of the same mass.
 This dependence is most readily seen in the bottom panel, which shows the
 ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bhlin$
\end_inset

 of high-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 samples divided by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bhlin$
\end_inset

 of low-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 samples.
 Thus in the bottom panel of Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:linear-bias"

\end_inset

, vertical axis values exceeding unity correspond to masses where high-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 halos cluster more strongly relative to their low-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 counterparts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the low-mass end, high-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 halos are more strongly clustered than low-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 halos of the same mass.
 The clustering difference increases with decreasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir,$
\end_inset

 and exceeds 
\begin_inset Formula $30\%$
\end_inset

 for halos of Milky Way mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir\approx10^{12}\msun.$
\end_inset

 At the high-mass end, the trend reverses, and the overall magnitude is
 weaker.
 These results are consistent with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wechsler06"

\end_inset

, who find that the same trends hold when the secondary halo property is
 NFW concentration, rather than 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax.$
\end_inset

 This agreement is to be expected: insofar as the halo profile is well-approxima
ted by an NFW profile, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 is entirely determined by concentration (see Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:vmax-mvir"

\end_inset

).
 Note that there is a drop in the ratio of the linear biases on the low-mass
 end.
 As we see no physical reason for this drop, we consider this to be a resolution
 effect and suggest that the completeness requirements for two-halo-property-dep
endent clustering are significantly more stringent relative to the requirements
 demanded by the need for a complete halo mass/velocity function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_biasVmax/linearBias_wText.pdf
	width 60col%

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:linear-bias"

\end_inset

Upper panel: Linear bias at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 as a function of halo mass from the Bolshoi and the MultiDark simulations.
 The vertical dashed line indicates the upper/lower limit of halo mass for
 the Bolshoi/MultiDark simulations respectively.
 The blue lines correspond to a linear bias for high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos, while the green lines correspond to low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos.
 The solid lines correspond to the full halo sample while the dashed line
 corresponds to the sample where ejected halos are removed.
 Lower panel: Ratio of linear biases between high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 and low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 samples from the Bolshoi and the MultiDark simulations.
 The clustering difference increases with decreasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir,$
\end_inset

 and exceeds 
\begin_inset Formula $30\%$
\end_inset

 for halos of Milky Way mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir\approx10^{12}\msun.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, we study the scale-dependence of halo bias on small scales for high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 and low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos.
 We wish to parse the novel, small-scale effects from the well-known large-scale
 effects.
 So for each sample of high- and low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos, we compute the following quantity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{b}_{{\rm h}}(r|\mvir;\vmax)\equiv b_{{\rm h}}(r|\mvir;\vmax)/b_{{\rm lin}}(\mvir;\vmax).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Thus for any sample of halos, as 
\begin_inset Formula $r\gtrsim10\mpch,$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{{\rm h}}(r)\rightarrow1,$
\end_inset

 by construction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The top panel of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:small-scale"

\end_inset

 shows the ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{b}_{h}(r)$
\end_inset

 of high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 samples divided by 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{h}(r)$
\end_inset

 of low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 samples for several mass bins.
 The first three mass bins labeled in the figure, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{11.7,12.0,12.2}h^{-1}{\rm {\rm M_{\odot}}}$
\end_inset

, are from the Bolshoi simulation, and the last two mass bins, 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}=10^{12.7,13.1}h^{-1}{\rm {\rm M_{\odot}}}$
\end_inset

, are from the MultiDark simulation.
 High-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos cluster more strongly compared to their low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 counterparts at 
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

.
 This scale-dependent feature becomes stronger with decreasing 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 and exceeds 40% for halos of Milky Way mass and reaches 60% at 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}\approx10^{11.7}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the reverse trend at small scales 
\begin_inset Formula $r<1h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

, where low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos seem to cluster more strongly, is an artifact of the normalization
 by the linear biases.
 The ratio without normalization goes to one at small scales.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Up until present, we have used both host halos and ejected halos to compute
 halo biases.
 Both types of halos are identified as distinct halos at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 Ejected halos, however, are halos which were identified as part of more
 massive halos at one or more occasions in the past, but were ejected and
 now exist as a host halo at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

.
 Those ejected halos tend to exist around more massive halos (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wetzel_etal13,wang09"

\end_inset

).
 Therefore, the effect on scale-dependent biases may be caused by those
 ejected halos.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To test this ejected halo hypothesis, we compute halo-matter cross correlation
 functions after first excluding the subpopulation of ejected halos.
 Our results for the linear regime are shown as the dashed curves in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:linear-bias"

\end_inset

.
 The relative difference in the linear bias between high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 and low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos is suppressed to 25% for halos of Milky Way mass.
 This suppression due to excluding the ejected halos is consistent with
 the results presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wang09"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the bottom panel of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:small-scale"

\end_inset

, we show the scale-dependence of assembly bias for non-ejected halos.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The mass resolution of the MultiDark simulation makes it challenging to
 identify ejected halos with high completeness.
 We therefore restrict ourselves to the Bolshoi simulation in the bottom
 panel of Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:small-scale"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Once the ejected halos have been removed, the scale-dependent feature of
 assembly bias is greatly reduced.
 This implies an intimate connection between the scale-dependence of assembly
 bias and subhalo back-splashing (see Sec.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:discussion"

\end_inset

 for further discussion).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_biasVmax/Both_smallScale_wang_log.pdf
	lyxscale 50
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_biasVmax/Bolshoi_smallScale_wang_log_nonEject.pdf
	lyxscale 50
	width 50col%

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:small-scale"

\end_inset

 Top panel: Ratio of halo-matter cross correlation functions between high/low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos from the Bolshoi simulation and the MultiDark simulation at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

, normalized by their linear biases.
 Each line corresponds to different halo mass bins labeled in the plots.
 The top three lines that correspond to low mass halos are computed from
 halos in the Bolshoi simulation, while the bottom lines are from the MultiDark
 simulation.
 Those plots show that high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos cluster more strongly than low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos at 
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 and the relative scale-dependence between those subsamples increases smoothly
 with decreasing halo mass.
 Bottom panel: The same figure as the top panel without ejected halos only
 from the Bolshoi simulation.
 As can be seen by comparing these results to those in the top panel, the
 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

-dependence of halo bias on small scales is dramatically reduced by excluding
 ejected subhalos.
 This implies an intimate connection between the scale-dependence of assembly
 bias and subhalo back-splashing.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Observational Consequences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now consider possible observational consequences of the results of the
 previous section.
 In order to do this, the key first step is to relate an observable property
 of a galaxy (luminosity, stellar mass) to an intrinsic property of its
 host halo (mass, circular velocity).
 As one might infer from above (and we demonstrate below), different choices
 for the latter can result in significant differences for different observables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to be explicit, we use the abundance matching technique 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kravtsov04a,vale_ostriker04,vale_ostriker06,tasitsiomi_etal04,conroy_wechsler09,guo10,simha10,neistein11a,watson_etal12b,rod_puebla12,hearin_etal12b,kravtsov13,saito15"

\end_inset

 to connect the stellar masses of central galaxies to either the mass or
 circular velocity of host halos.
 We implement this by splitting the halo catalog into a series of bins with
 constant number density (=
\begin_inset Formula $1.6\times10^{-3}(h^{-1}{\rm Mpc})^{-3}$
\end_inset

), rank ordering either by mass or circular velocity.
 We label each bin by its corresponding stellar mass, computed from the
 stellar-to-halo mass relation of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "behroozi13"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that when we rank order based on circular velocity, there is the possibilit
y that the mean halo masses of these bins could differ from what we obtain
 after rank ordering by halo mass.
 We explicitly check this and find that the mean halo masses for both cases
 agree to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim99.6\%$
\end_inset

, allowing us to consistently compare samples of mock central galaxies with
 the same stellar mass, but where the stellar mass is statistically regulated
 by either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find only a relatively minor difference in the large-scale clustering
 of the two samples of mock central galaxies.
 At fixed stellar mass, the linear bias of samples selected by their circular
 velocity are 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim5\%$
\end_inset

 higher than samples selected by halo mass.
 This decreases to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim2\%$
\end_inset

 if we remove ejected halos from both samples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We study the scale-dependence of the clustering of our mock central galaxies
 in Fig.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:abundance_small"

\end_inset

, which is directly analogous to Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:small-scale"

\end_inset

, only here we have use the abundance matching technique described above
 to illustrate how our 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

halo-level" results may manifest in observed galaxy populations.
 Again we see a clear scale-dependence of the clustering signal, with a
 maximum difference of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim15\%$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim1h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "reed07"

\end_inset

.
 These differences go down to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim5\%$
\end_inset

 after removing ejected subhalos, again reflecting the intimate connection
 between scale-dependent assembly bias and subhalo back-splashing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_biasVmax/Bolshoi_andrew_smallScale.pdf
	lyxscale 50
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_biasVmax/Bolshoi_andrew_smallScale_nonEj.pdf
	lyxscale 50
	width 50col%

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:abundance_small"

\end_inset

Ratio of halo-matter cross correlation functions between 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

-based and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

-based abundance matching samples with ejected halos (top) and without ejected
 halos (bottom).
 The ratios are normalized by their linear biases.
 Each line corresponds to different stellar mass bins labeled in the plots.
 With ejected halos, the halo biases computed from the 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

-selected samples have very different scale-dependence than the ones from
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

-selected samples.
 By removing those ejected halos, the difference is reduced by threefold.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:discussion"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For halos 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}\gtrsim\mcoll\approx10^{12.8}\msun,$
\end_inset

 we have shown that the linear bias of low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos is larger relative to high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos of the same mass.
 As shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dalal_etal08"

\end_inset

, this phenomenon is nicely explained in terms of the statistics of fluctuations
 in a Gaussian random field.
 Consider two halos with the same present-day mass, but with different concentra
tion.
 Both halos originate from a fluctuation of the same peak height, but with
 different peak curvature: the high-concentration (high-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

) halo has a sharper peak than the low-concentration (low-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

) halo.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dalal_etal08"

\end_inset

 showed that a generic prediction of Extended Press Schechter theory (EPS)
 with a configuration space filter is that low-curvature peaks cluster more
 strongly relative to high-curvature peaks of the same height.
 In closely related work, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "zentner07"

\end_inset

 used EPS with a configuration space filter to show that for a pair of halos
 of the same peak height, the early-forming halo should reside in a denser
 large-scale environment than the late-forming one.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Chapter IX, Section D.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A critical assumption underlying these EPS predictions is that a halo is
 the dominant peak in its large-scale environment.
 This is a well-founded assumption at the high-mass end, and we see that
 the predictions are in good agreement with simulations in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir>\mcoll$
\end_inset

 regime 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dalal_etal08"

\end_inset

.
 The situation is quite different when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir\lesssim\mcoll.$
\end_inset

 We have confirmed previous results (e.g., 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wechsler06"

\end_inset

) that large-scale assembly bias changes sign and strengthens for lower-mass
 halos.
 This is in stark contrast to the EPS model described above, which makes
 the same prediction for assembly bias regardless of halo mass.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus EPS succeeds and fails in precisely the regimes where we expect.
 Lower-mass halos are strongly influenced by the tidal field in which they
 evolve 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hahn_etal07b,wang_etal11,shi15,hahn_etal09,hearin_etal15"

\end_inset

; the EPS assumption that the halo dominates its environment breaks down
 catastrophically, and in this regime nonlinear evolution governs assembly
 bias.
 On the other hand, high-mass halos 
\shape italic
do
\shape default
 dominate their tidal environment; the EPS assumption holds good, and we
 can understand assembly bias as naturally arising from the statistics of
 Gaussian fluctuations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our results on the scale-dependence of assembly bias are also consistent
 with this picture.
 First, we remind the reader that halo bias for high-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 halos shows non-trivial scale dependence with a pronounced bump at 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim1-2\mpch$
\end_inset

 compared to the bias for low-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 halos.
 This scale-dependent feature for high-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 halos becomes 60% larger compared to low-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 halos at 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir}}\approx10^{11.7}\msun$
\end_inset

.
 This feature, however, is removed by excluding the ejected halos, implying
 that this special sub-population is responsible for the scale-dependent
 bump.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This scale-dependence has a simple interpretation in terms of subhalo back-splas
hing.
 First, ejected halos are physically associated with the more massive halo
 from which they were ejected.
 The clustering of ejected halos is therefore largely determined by this
 associated massive halo, much like the clustering of present-day subhalos
 is determined by their host halo.
 Second, as ejected halos pass near and inside a massive halo, their physical
 growth is arrested, and many such halos even experience substantial mass
 loss 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wang09,sinha12,wetzel_etal13,sinha15"

\end_inset

.
 This arrested development has a greater impact on the outer layers of the
 halo, so that the ejected halo's mass is significantly more affected than
 its circular velocity 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "behroozi13c"

\end_inset

.
 Putting these two effects together, we should naturally expect the outskirts
 of massive groups and clusters to be preferentially populated with low-mass
 halos that have above-average values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 for their mass.
 This manifests in the scale-dependent bump shown in Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:small-scale"

\end_inset

 & 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:abundance_small"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent advances in our understanding of halo growth sheds further light
 on the above results.
 As shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "diemer14,adhikari14,wetzel_nagai14,more15"

\end_inset

, the natural physical boundary of a dark matter halo is the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

splashback radius", which is the radius where accreted matter reaches its
 first apocenter after turnaround, and is roughly 
\begin_inset Formula $2-3\rvir.$
\end_inset

 As shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wetzel_etal13"

\end_inset

, the halos of massive groups and clusters (
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir\gtrsim10^{13}\msun,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\rvir\gtrsim500\kpch$
\end_inset

) are surrounded by a large fraction of ejected halos.
 For ejected halos with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir\approx10^{11.7}h^{-1}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 halos, the host-centric spatial distribution of the ejected population
 peaks at 
\begin_inset Formula $r\approx1.25R_{{\rm 200m}}\approx1.5\mpch$
\end_inset

 (see Figs.
 2 and 3 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wetzel_etal13"

\end_inset

).
 The bump feature we find at 
\begin_inset Formula $1-2\mpch$
\end_inset

 is therefore in quantitative agreement with the results 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wetzel_etal13,wang_mo_jing08"

\end_inset

: this bump occurs at the same physical scale that we would expect if the
 clustering of the ejected population is largely determined by the host
 to which the halos are ultimately bound.
 Note that the assembly bias on large scales, 
\begin_inset Formula $r\gtrsim10\mpch,$
\end_inset

 is not dominated by the ejected halos, which is consistent with 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wang_mo_jing08"

\end_inset

.
 Without the ejected halos, the relative difference in the linear bias between
 high-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 and low-
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}$
\end_inset

 halos remains 25% for halos of Milky Way mass.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to explore possible observational consequences of our findings,
 we use abundance matching relating a stellar mass of central galaxies to
 either mass or circular velocity of host halos.
 Using different intrinsic properties for host halos results in significant
 differences in clustering signals of central galaxies.
 On large scales, the linear bias of samples selected by their circular
 velocities are 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim5\%$
\end_inset

 higher than samples selected by halo masses at fixed stellar mass.
 Without the ejected halos, this differences is reduced to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim2\%$
\end_inset

.
 On small scales (
\begin_inset Formula $r<10h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

), samples selected by their circular velocities exhibit the scale dependence
 with a bump at 
\begin_inset Formula $1-2h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 compared to samples selected by halo masses.
 This scale-dependent bump for 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max}}-$
\end_inset

selected samples becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim15\%$
\end_inset

 with the ejected halos and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim5\%$
\end_inset

 without the ejected halos.
 As these effects are roughly as large as existing SDSS clustering measurements
 on these scales, this raises the possibility that clustering measurements
 can be used to determine which host halo property is the true statistical
 regulator of the stellar mass of the central galaxy residing in the halo.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "section:summary"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We conclude the paper with an overview of our primary results:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
At fixed mass 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir,$
\end_inset

 the large-scale bias of halos exhibits significant residual dependence
 on potential well depth 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax.$
\end_inset

 At the low-mass end, high-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 halos cluster more strongly than their low-
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax$
\end_inset

 counterparts.
 At the high-mass end, this trend reverses, and is generally weaker, with
 the transition occurring at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mcoll\approx10^{12.5}\msun.$
\end_inset

 Our results are quantitatively consistent with previous studies of large-scale
 halo assembly bias.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We show that assembly bias exhibits complex scale-dependence.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\vmax-$
\end_inset

dependence of halo clustering shows a pronounced 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bump" on scales 
\begin_inset Formula $500\kpch\lesssim r\lesssim5\mpch.$
\end_inset

 This scale-dependence is itself mass-dependent: the bump feature is strongest
 for low-mass halos and vanishes for halos with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir\gtrsim\mcoll.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The scale-dependence of assembly bias can primarily be attributed to a special
 sub-population of 
\shape italic
ejected subhalos
\shape default
, which experience arrested mass-growth before and after being ejected from
 a higher-mass host.
 If this special population is excluded from the halo sample, the strength
 of small-scale assembly bias is limited to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lesssim5\%$
\end_inset

 for all masses 
\begin_inset Formula $\mvir\gtrsim10^{11.75}\msun.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Efficient Construction of Mock Catalogs for Baryon Acoustic Oscillation
 Surveys
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Precision measurements of the large scale structure of the Universe require
 large numbers of high fidelity mock catalogs to accurately assess, and
 account for, the presence of systematic effects.
 We introduce and test a scheme for generating mock catalogs rapidly using
 suitably derated N-body simulations.
 Our aim is to reproduce the large scale structure and the gross properties
 of dark matter halos with high accuracy, while sacrificing the details
 of the halo's internal structure.
 By adjusting global and local time-steps in an N-body code, we demonstrate
 that we recover halo masses to better than 
\begin_inset Formula $2\%$
\end_inset

 and the power spectrum (both in real and redshift space, for 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

) to better than 
\begin_inset Formula $1\%$
\end_inset

, while requiring a factor of 4 less CPU time.
 We also calibrate the redshift spacing of outputs required to generate
 simulated light cones.
 We find that outputs separated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta z=0.05$
\end_inset

 allow us to interpolate particle positions and velocities to reproduce
 the real and redshift space power spectra to better than 
\begin_inset Formula $1\%$
\end_inset

 (out to 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

).
 We apply these ideas to generate a suite of simulations spanning a range
 of cosmologies, motivated by the Baryon Oscillation Spectroscopic Survey
 (BOSS) but broadly applicable to future large scale structure surveys including
 eBOSS and DESI.
 As an initial demonstration of the utility of such simulations, we calibrate
 the shift in the baryonic acoustic oscillation peak position as a function
 of galaxy bias with higher precision than has been possible so far.
 This paper also serves to document the simulations, which we make publicly
 available.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Large-volume spectroscopic surveys of the Universe 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013arXiv1305.5422S,2000AJ....120.1579Y,2011MNRAS.415.2876B"

\end_inset

 are revolutionizing our understanding of cosmology and structure formation.
 Based on these successes, a new generation of surveys 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013arXiv1308.0847L,2013arXiv1305.5422S,2011arXiv1110.3193L"

\end_inset

 is being planned that will improve cosmological constraints by an order
 of magnitude (or more).
 This unprecedented increase in statistical precision places stringent demands
 on the underlying theoretical modeling and analysis techniques; numerical
 simulations will play an essential role in meeting these requirements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One set of challenges for simulations arise from the varied roles they play,
 and the different requirements these impose in turn on the simulations.
 At one extreme, simulations are necessary for estimating the errors on
 the measurements.
 This typically requires very large volumes to simulate entire surveys thousands
 of times, but have lower accuracy requirements.
 Motivated by these considerations, a number of recent studies have investigated
 methods designed to produce mock catalogs with reduced accuracy, but much
 higher throughput compared to full N-body simulations
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2002ApJ...564....8M,2002MNRAS.331..587M,2008MNRAS.391..435F,   2013AN....334..691R,2013arXiv1312.2013C,2013JCAP...06..036T,2014MNRAS.437.2594W,   2013MNRAS.433.2389M,2001A&A...367...18H,2009ApJ...701..945S,2014MNRAS.439L..21K,2014arXiv1409.1124C"

\end_inset

.
 The effect of changing the input cosmology used to generate the covariance
 matrix on cosmological inferences is still not fully understood, nor is
 it clear how best to implement such variations (but see Refs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Morrison2013"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kalus2015"

\end_inset

 for recent work on this topic).
 More recently, the impact of super-survey modes (modes outside the survey
 volume) on inferred errors has been shown to be potentially larger than
 previously appreciated (e.g., Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013PhRvD..87l3504T"

\end_inset

) and is an area of active study.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At the other extreme, simulations are crucial for calibrating the theoretical
 models used to fit the data.
 Examples here are quantifying shifts in the baryon acoustic oscillation
 distance scale due to nonlinear evolution and galaxy bias 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2008ApJ...686...13S,2008PhRvD..77b3533C,2008PhRvD..77d3525S,2009PhRvD..80f3508P,2010ApJ...720.1650S,2012PhRvD..85j3523S"

\end_inset

, or templates used to fit the full shape of the galaxy correlation function.
 For such applications, one ideally requires high fidelity simulations.
 The volume requirements are significantly reduced from that for covariance
 matrices, but the simulations still need to cover volumes much larger than
 survey volumes to keep systematic errors below statistical errors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An intermediate application is the generation of mock catalogs that capture
 the observational characteristics of surveys (e.g., geometry, selection effects).
 The importance of these cannot be underestimated, since the effects of
 many observational systematics can only be quantitatively estimated by
 simulating them.
 These issues will become progressively more important for the next generations
 of surveys which will move away from highly complete and pure samples that
 have mostly been used for cosmological studies to date.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest way to generate approximate density fields is to use analytic
 approximations such as Lagrangian perturbation theory followed by prescriptions
 that place halos within the density field to match the halo distribution
 measured in N-body simulations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013MNRAS.428.1036M,2014arXiv1401.4171M"

\end_inset

, or simply to run lower resolution N-body codes with a small number of
 time-steps 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013JCAP...06..036T"

\end_inset

, or a combination of the two approaches 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2014MNRAS.437.2594W"

\end_inset

.
 These methods are successful in capturing the large-scale density field
 but lose information on small scales.
 Because of their speed, they can be used to produce large numbers of simulation
s required to build sample covariance matrices, at error levels ranging
 from 
\begin_inset Formula $5-10\%$
\end_inset

 (depending on the quantities being predicted).
 It is difficult to estimate, however, what the loss of accuracy implies
 for tests of systematic errors, which may need to be modeled at the 
\begin_inset Formula $<1\%$
\end_inset

 level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The approach we take here is to reduce the small spatial scale accuracy
 of a high-resolution N-body code by coarsening its temporal resolution.
 For the code we consider, the time-stepping consists of two components,
 (i) a long time step for solving for the evolution under the long-range
 particle-mesh (PM) force, and (ii) a set of underlying sub-cycled time
 steps for a short-range particle-particle interaction, computed either
 via a tree-based algorithm, or by direct particle-particle force evaluations.
 The idea is to reduce the number of both types of time steps while preserving
 enough accuracy to correctly describe the large scale distribution of galaxies,
 as modeled by a halo occupation distribution (HOD) approach.
 One goal in this paper is, therefore, to quantitatively understand the
 impact of the temporal resolution on the halo density field and how to
 accurately reproduce the details of the halo density field on large scales,
 while sacrificing small scale structure information.
 Doing this successfully allows us to generate a suite of large volume simulatio
ns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having determined the optimal time-stepping that maintains accuracy on the
 scales of interest, we then generate a suite of simulations using this
 procedure.
 We use these simulations to demonstrate two example applications discussed
 above.
 The first example addresses the generation of mock catalogs for spectroscopic
 surveys.
 We focus on the Baryon Oscillation Spectroscopic Survey (BOSS), although
 these simulations can be used to simulate aspects of future surveys such
 as eBOSS and DESI.
 The gains from optimizing our time-stepping allow us to simulate a volume
 large enough to embed two entire BOSS volumes into the same simulation.
 As part of building these mock catalogs, we also consider the frequency
 with which we need to store snapshots of the N-body simulation in order
 to include light-cone effects in the mocks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our second application highlights the usefulness of these techniques for
 constraining systematic effects: we use the simulations to constrain shifts
 in the BAO acoustic scale as a function of halo bias.
 This requires very large volumes to statistically measure the shifts, while
 at the same time, one must robustly determine the halo properties as well.
 Although we restrict ourselves here to a simple demonstration, our results
 show an unambiguous shift in the BAO scale due to a combination of nonlinear
 evolution of the density field, as well as halo bias.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The paper is organized as follows.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:hacc"

\end_inset

 briefly describes the Hardware/Hybrid Accelerated Cosmology Code (HACC)
 N-body framework we use to generate our simulations, focusing on the flexibilit
y in the time-stepping that we exploit here.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:time"

\end_inset

 presents a sequence of convergence tests where we evaluate the effects
 of time-stepping on the halo density field.
 Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:light cones"

\end_inset

 discusses interpolation between saved time steps, necessary for constructing
 light cone outputs.
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:boss"

\end_inset

 presents the two example applications of the simulations; we conclude in
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:disc"

\end_inset

 by outlining possible future directions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All simulations and calculations in this paper assume a 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

CDM cosmology with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{m}=0.2648$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\Lambda}=0.7352$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{b}h^{2}=0.02258$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{s}=0.963$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{8}=0.8$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0.71$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Coarse-Graining in Time with HACC
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:hacc"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All simulations in this paper were carried out using the Hardware/Hybrid
 Accelerated Cosmology Code (HACC) framework.
 HACC provides an advanced, architecture-agile, extreme-scale N-body capability
 targeted to cosmological simulations.
 In this Section, we describe how HACC's hierarchical time-stepping scheme
 can be easily used to implement coarse-graining in time so as to reduce
 the CPU time but maintaining acceptable accuracy for halo statistics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The HACC Framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
HACC is descended from an approach originally developed for the heterogeneous
 architecture of Roadrunner 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1742-6596-180-1-012019,Pope:2010:AU:1845737.1845828"

\end_inset

, the first supercomputer to break the petaflop performance barrier.
 HACC's flexible code architecture combines MPI with a variety of more local
 programming models, (e.g., OpenCL, OpenMP) and is easily adaptable to different
 platforms.
 HACC has demonstrated scaling on the entire IBM BG/Q Sequoia system up
 to 1,572,864 cores with an equal number of MPI ranks, attaining 13.94 PFlops
 at 69.2% of peak and 90% parallel efficiency (for details, see Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2012arXiv1211.4864H"

\end_inset

).
 Examples of science results obtained using HACC include 64-billion particle
 runs for baryon acoustic oscillations predictions for the BOSS Lyman-
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 forest 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2010ApJ...713..383W"

\end_inset

, high-statistics predictions for the halo profiles of massive clusters
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013ApJ...766...32B"

\end_inset

, and 0.55 and 1.1
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

trillion particle runs at high mass resolution
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Heitmann2014"

\end_inset

.
 A recent overview of the HACC framework can be found in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "hacc_2014"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
HACC uses a hybrid parallel algorithmic structure, splitting the force calculati
on into a specially designed grid-based long/medium range spectral particle
 mesh (PM) component that is common to all computer architectures, and an
 architecture-specific short-range solver.
 Modular code design combined with particle caching allows the short-range
 solvers to be `hot-swappable' on-node; they are blind to the parallel implement
ation of the long-range solver.
 The short-range solvers can use direct particle-particle interactions,
 i.e., a P
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

M algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1988csup.book.....H"

\end_inset

, as on (Cell or GPU) accelerated systems, or use tree methods on conventional
 or many-core architectures.
 (This was the case for the simulations reported here.) In all cases, the
 time-stepping scheme is based on a symplectic method with (adaptive) sub-cyclin
g of the short-range force.
 The availability of multiple algorithms within the HACC framework allows
 us to carry out careful error analyses, for example, the P
\begin_inset Formula $^{3}$
\end_inset

M and the TreePM versions agree to within 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1\%$
\end_inset

 for the nonlinear power spectrum test in the code comparison suite of Ref.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2005ApJS..160...28H"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
HACC Time Stepping Scheme
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As already discussed, an important feature of the work presented here is
 the ability to carry out error-controlled approximate simulations at high
 throughput.
 In order to understand how to implement this, we provide some details on
 the HACC time-stepping algorithm.
 In HACC, time evolution is viewed as a symplectic map on phase space: 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta(t)=\exp(-t{\bf {H}})\zeta(0)$
\end_inset

 where, 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 is a phase-space vector 
\begin_inset Formula $({\bf x},{\bf v})$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is the (self-consistent) Hamiltonian, and the operator, 
\begin_inset Formula ${\bf {H}}=[H,~]_{P}$
\end_inset

, denotes the action of taking the Poisson bracket with the Hamiltonian.
 Suppose that the Hamiltonian can be written as the sum of two parts; then
 by using the Campbell-Baker-Hausdorff (CBH) series we can build an integrator
 for the time evolution; repeated application of the CBH formula yields
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\exp[-t({\bf {H}}_{1}+{\bf {H}}_{2})]=\exp[-(t/2){\bf {H}}_{1}]\exp(-t{\bf {H}}_{2})\exp[-(t/2){\bf {H}}_{1}]+O(t^{3}),
\]

\end_inset

a second order symplectic integrator.
 In the basic PM application, the Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the free particle (kinetic) piece while 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the one-particle effective potential; corresponding respectively to
 the `stream' and `kick' maps 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}=\exp(-t{\bf {H}}_{1})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{2}=\exp(-t{\bf {H}}_{2})$
\end_inset

.
 In the stream map, the particle position is drifted using its known velocity,
 which remains unchanged; in the kick map, the velocity is updated using
 the force evaluation, while the position remains unchanged.
 This symmetric `split-operator' step is termed SKS (stream-kick-stream).
 A KSK scheme constitutes an alternative second-order symplectic integrator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the presence of both short and long-range forces, we split the Hamiltonian
 into two parts, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{1}=H_{sr}+H_{lr}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{sr}$
\end_inset

 contains the kinetic and particle-particle force interaction (with an associate
d map 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{sr}$
\end_inset

), whereas, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{2}=H_{lr}$
\end_inset

 is just the long range force, corresponding to the map 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{lr}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the long range force varies relatively slowly, we construct a single
 time-step map by sub-cycling 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{sr}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{full}(t)=M_{lr}(t/2)[M_{sr}(t/n_{c})]^{n_{c}}M_{lr}(t/2)$
\end_inset

, the total map being a usual second-order symplectic integrator.
 This corresponds to a KSK step, where the S is not an exact stream step,
 but has enough 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{sr}$
\end_inset

 steps composed together to obtain the required accuracy.
 (We take care that the time-dependence in the self-consistent potential
 is treated correctly; HACC uses the scale factor, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, as the time variable.) The code therefore has two degrees of freedom to
 tune its time-steps: the length of the full time step (
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 above), and the number of sub-cycles for the short range force (
\begin_inset Formula $n_{c}$
\end_inset

 above).
 As discussed later below, we will use the flexibility in the sub-cycling
 as a way of reducing the number of time steps such that the loss of accuracy
 only affects the resolution at very small scales, which, as discussed previousl
y, are not of interest in the current set of simulations.
 For high-resolution applications, HACC allows for particle-level adaptive
 time-stepping, but that feature is not exploited here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Time Step Tuning and Halo Matching
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:time"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we systematically examine how reducing the number of global
 time steps affects individual gross halo properties (i.e., halo masses, positions
, and velocities), as well as aggregate statistics such as the halo mass
 function and spatial clustering.
 We run a set of convergence tests with boxes of size 
\begin_inset Formula $(256h^{-1}{\rm Mpc})^{3}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $256^{3}$
\end_inset

 particles.
 These runs have a similar particle mass as the full 
\begin_inset Formula $(4000h^{-1}{\rm Mpc})^{3}$
\end_inset

 volume simulations we present later.
 We run these with the following time step options : 450/5, 300/3, 300/2,
 150/3 and 150/2 where the first number is the number of long time-steps,
 while the second is the number of subcycles.
 The 450/5 case has been independently verified to give fully converged
 results and is the baseline against which we compare all other results.
 Each simulation is started from the same initial condition and evolved
 down to 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.15$
\end_inset

.
 We demonstrate that the 300/2 case, corresponding to a time step of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta a\approx0.003$
\end_inset

 reproduces the full resolution simulation for all the large scale properties
 we consider, and is our choice for the mock catalogs presented in Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:boss"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Halo Matching Algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to compare detailed halo properties, we need to match individual
 halos between our reference 450/5 run and test runs with reduced time steps.
 All simulations share the same particle initial conditions, allowing us
 to match halos in different runs by matching their individual particle
 content.
 Given a halo in simulation A, we consider all halos in simulation B that
 between them hold all the particles belonging to the halo in simulation
 A.
 Given this list of possible matches, we choose the halo in run B with the
 largest number of common particles with the reference halo in run A.
 To avoid spurious matches, we also require that the fraction of common
 particles (relative to simulation A) exceeds a given threshold.
 To illustrate how this matching algorithm works, we use the samples from
 the 300/2 simulation and the 450/5 simulation, and adopt a threshold of
 50% as our default choice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The matching algorithm described above is unidirectional -- multiple halos
 in run A may have particles resident in a single halo in run B.
 In our simulations, this happens at the 1-2% level, adopting a particle
 matching threshold of 50%.
 We refer to these cases as `multiply-booked' halos.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mass-scatter1"

\end_inset

 compares halo masses when matching the 450/5 simulation to the 300/2 simulation
 for the case of multiply-booked halos, as well as the rest.
 The top left panel shows the mass scatter for all the matched halos between
 the two simulations, while the top right panel shows the mass scatter only
 for the halos that have one-to-one correspondence.
 The bottom left panel shows the mass scatter for individual multiply-booked
 halos, while the bottom right panel plots the summed halo mass for the
 corresponding halos.
 The overall behavior represented in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mass-scatter1"

\end_inset

 is straightforward to interpret.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_HACC/testDB_mass_300_2_z0_15.pdf
	width 46.5col%

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_HACC/testDB_nonDB_300_2_z0_15.pdf
	width 53.5col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_HACC/testDB_DB_numPartCut_300_2_z0_15.pdf
	width 46.5text%

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_HACC/testDB_sum_mass_f0_5_300_2_z0_15.pdf
	width 53.5col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:mass-scatter1"

\end_inset

Comparing the halo mass of matched halos in the 450/5 simulation (x-axis)
 to the 300/2 simulation (y-axis) at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.15$
\end_inset

.
 Panels correspond to halos with different matching criteria imposed: all
 the matched halos (top left), the vast majority of matched halos having
 one-to-one correspondence (top right), matched halos not having one-to-one
 correspondence called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

multiply-booked
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 halos (bottom left), and the multiply-booked halos whose corresponding
 halo masses are added (bottom right).
 The color bar on the right indicates the corresponding color to the number
 of halos in the plot.
 The results shown in these panels imply that the low-mass scatter between
 the 450/5 simulation and the 300/2 simulation shown in the top left panel
 arises when physically associated halos in the 450/5 simulation are merged
 into one halo in the 300/2 simulation due to an effectively worse resolution
 in the latter case.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the top left panel shows, there are low-mass halos in the 450/5 simulation
 matched to high-mass halos in the 300/2 simulation.
 The same trend is observed for the case of multiply-booked halos (bottom
 left panel), but not for the one-to-one matched halos (top right).
 Furthermore, the disagreement for halo masses between the two simulations
 are resolved by adding the corresponding halo masses.
 This implies that there are multiple halos in the 450/5 simulation which
 are merged into one halo in the 300/2 simulation.
 The smaller number of time steps in the 300/2 simulations reduces substructure
 as well as the compactness of the halos compared to the 450/5 simulation.
 Thus, for a small fraction of halos in the 450/5 simulation, individual
 halos can be merged into a single halo in the 300/2 simulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mass-content"

\end_inset

 shows the number densities of the unmatched halos in the 450/5 simulation
 when compared to the 300/2 simulation at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.15$
\end_inset

.
 There are three reasons that halos can turn up as unmatched.
 In the first case, particles forming a halo in simulation A may not form
 a component of a halo in simulation B (no common particles).
 Second, if the fraction of common particles over the total number of particles
 in each halo is less than the threshold of 50%, these halos will be eliminated
 from the matching set.
 Finally, for the case of multiply-booked halos, we remove all but the one
 with the largest number of common particles.
 In Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mass-content"

\end_inset

, we show each type of unmatched number density as a function of halo mass.
 The first case occurs only for low mass halos, where low effective resolution
 in a simulation can lead to halo drop out (halos are too 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fuzzy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to meet the Friends-of-Friends (FOF) connectivity criterion), and falls
 off steeply with rising halo mass.
 Most of the unmatched halos arise because they do not pass the threshold
 criterion.
 The fraction of unmatched halos due to being 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

multiply-booked
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is similar to the threshold case, albeit at a lower level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_HACC/unmatchHalo2_content_300_2_z0_15.pdf
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:mass-content"

\end_inset

 Itemization of unmatched halos (from the 450/5 and 300/2 simulations at
 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.15$
\end_inset

) shown as cumulative number densities of the unmatched halos arising from
 each procedure in the matching algorithm.
 The solid blue line is the total number density of the unmatched halos.
 The dashed green line shows halos with no counterpart -- none of the particles
 were identified as belonging to a halo in the comparison simulation; this
 is significant only at low halo mass.
 The dashed red line shows halos eliminated because of not meeting the matching
 threshold (i.e., the halos do not have enough of a fraction of the same particles
).
 The dashed yellow line is for the halos eliminated because multiple halos
 correspond to one halo (see text).
 The dashed blue line is the simulative number density of match halos as
 a reference.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The trends described above persist at different redshifts.
 As we reduce the number of total long timesteps taken, the unmatched fraction
 increases, due to the lower resolution of the simulations, while the number
 of sub-cycles does not noticeably change these results.
 In Section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

3.2 where we compare halo properties, we restrict ourselves to halos with
 a one-to-one correspondence (i.e., not multiply-booked halos).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Halo Properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now systematically compare halo properties (i.e., halo mass, position,
 and velocity) for halos in the lower resolution runs that were successfully
 matched to those in the 450/5 simulation.
 We are interested in correctly describing the large-scale distribution
 of galaxies using an HOD approach; this requires that only the dark matter
 halo locations and masses be estimated with sufficient accuracy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The comparison of halo masses for different time-stepping schemes to the
 450/5 simulation at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.15$
\end_inset

 is shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:HaloProperty_mass"

\end_inset

.
 We take all the matched halos whose masses are between 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{12.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13.0}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13.0}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14.0}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, and compute their means and standard deviations for 
\begin_inset Formula ${\rm M/M_{450/5}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{450/5}$
\end_inset

 is a halo mass for the 450/5 simulation and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a halo in the samples generated with different time-stepping
 schemes.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:HaloProperty_mass"

\end_inset

 shows that the simulations with small number of time steps produce systematical
ly lower FOF masses than the 450/5 simulation.
 (The same linking length (
\begin_inset Formula $b=0.168$
\end_inset

) is used in the FOF algorithm to define halos for all simulations.) For
 the case of the 300/2 simulation, the deviation from the FOF masses in
 the 450/5 simulation is about 1.7%, while for the case of the 150/3 and
 150/2 simulations, the deviations are about 5.7% and 8.5% respectively.
 The FOF masses are highest in the 450/5 simulation, decreasing systematically
 with increase in loss of temporal resolution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\color black
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_HACC/massSlice_z0_15.pdf
	width 50col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:HaloProperty_mass"

\end_inset

Comparison of halo mass (FOF, 
\begin_inset Formula $b=0.168$
\end_inset

) for matched halos between the 450/5 simulation and coarsened time-stepping
 schemes at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.15$
\end_inset

.
 We take all the matched halos whose masses are between 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{12.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13.0}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13.0}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13.5}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{14.0}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

, and compute the mean and the standard deviation for 
\begin_inset Formula ${M/M_{450/5}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{450/5}$
\end_inset

 is a halo mass for the 450/5 simulation and 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 stands for the simulations with different number of time steps corresponding
 to different colors in the plot.
 The dashed lines are the inverse of Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mass_adjust"

\end_inset

, which is a mass calibration formula for each simulation.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-positions have been displaced to avoid overlapping the error bars.
 Halo masses decrease systematically as the time resolution is coarsened.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:HaloProperty_step"

\end_inset

 shows the differences in positions (left panel) and velocities (right panel)
 for the matched halos at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.15$
\end_inset

.
 Simulations with a smaller number of global time steps (150) display significan
tly more scatter; they also show a small bias in the velocity.
 With 300 global time steps, the results are much improved; the velocity
 bias is almost entirely removed and the scatter is significantly reduced.
 The standard deviation in the differences in halo distances is matched
 to better than 
\begin_inset Formula $200h^{-1}{\rm kpc}$
\end_inset

 in these cases, and better than 
\begin_inset Formula $50{\rm km/s}$
\end_inset

 in velocities.
 As a reference, the standard deviation of velocities for the full resolution
 simulation (450/5) is about 
\begin_inset Formula $300{\rm km/s}$
\end_inset

.
 The distributions are very close to Gaussian, as shown by the dashed lines.
 As is clear from Figure
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:HaloProperty_step"

\end_inset

, the difference between 3 and 2 sub-cycles is insignificant for our purposes.
 We observe the same trends for the halo properties discussed here at different
 redshifts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mass-content"

\end_inset

, the fraction of unmatched halos in the 300/2 simulation to the 450/5 simulatio
n is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $5\%$
\end_inset

 over most of the halo mass ranges, which implies that the 300/2 simulation
 has almost the same number of halos as the 450/5 simulation.
 Furthermore, Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:mass-scatter1"

\end_inset

 shows that most of the halos in the 300/2 simulation have the same mass
 as the ones in the 450/5 simulation.
 Since the number of sub-cycles only affects the halo positions and velocities
 at a low level, as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:HaloProperty_step"

\end_inset

, we choose the 300/2 time step to save simulation time while keeping the
 halo properties almost identical to the 450/5 simulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
