\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset

Left: Comparison of the velocity component 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{x}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.2$
\end_inset

 before and after linear interpolation.
 We estimate velocities at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.2$
\end_inset

 by linearly interpolating velocities at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.25$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.15$
\end_inset

.
 The blue line shows the original scatter of the velocities between 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.25$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.2$
\end_inset

, while the green line shows the scatter after linear interpolation.
 Right: The ratio of the power spectrum of the shifted halos to its expected
 value in redshift space.
 We shift halos from 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.25$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.2$
\end_inset

 and use original velocities at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.25$
\end_inset

 (blue line) and the linearly interpolated velocities (green line) to define
 redshift space.
 The denominator is the redshift space cross power spectrum at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.2$
\end_inset

, which is the expected value after shifting.
 As a reference, the result of shifting from 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.25$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.2$
\end_inset

 in real space is shown as a dashed line.
 We recover the expected power spectrum to better than 
\begin_inset Formula $1\%$
\end_inset

 out to 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0.8h{\rm Mpc}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 by linearly interpolating velocities.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

