\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:disc"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The precision measurements expected from current and future galaxy spectroscopic
 surveys to test the expansion and structure formation history of the Universe
 require an accurate understanding of systematic effects.
 To explore these effects, large-volume N-body simulations with acceptable
 accuracy are required.
 De-tuning high-resolution N-body codes by coarse-graining the time stepping
 offers a way to generate these simulations at lower computational cost.
 In this paper we have presented a quantitative study of the impact of time
 step sizes on the halo and matter density fields using the HACC code.
 HACC has two adjustable time stepping parameters -- a global time step
 and sub-cycle steps to track particle trajectories on small scales.
 We consider cases where we increase the length of each time step by factors
 of 1.5 and 3 respectively, as well as reducing the number of sub-cycles.
 We find that the number of sub-cycles makes almost no difference to any
 of our final results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our fiducial choice is to use 300 global time steps corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta a(z)=0.003$
\end_inset

 and 2 sub-cycles (increasing the length of the global time step by a factor
 of 1.5 and that of the sub-cycles by a factor of 2.5), resulting in a reduction
 of the simulation run times by a factor of four.
 We keep the mass resolution constant; the results here are based on a particle
 mass of 
\begin_inset Formula $6.86\times10^{10}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 We summarize the key results below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(a) Halo masses are underestimated because reducing the number of time steps
 produces halos with less substructure and a more diffuse distribution of
 mass.
 We demonstrate that this can be corrected with higher fidelity simulations,
 recovering the halo masses to 98% fidelity.
 The halo mass function is correctly recovered for masses above 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{12.7}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 100 particles per halo.
 We run the halo finder with identical parameters as in the full resolution
 runs for simplicity.
 It may however be possible to get further improvements by changing the
 parameters of the halo finder, as was done in Ref.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2013MNRAS.428.1036M"

\end_inset

.
 We leave an exploration of this for future work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(b) The halo positions and velocities are recovered with a scatter of 
\begin_inset Formula $0.08h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $12.8{\rm km/s}$
\end_inset

 respectively, ensuring that their large scale distributions are unaffected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(c) The clustering of halos is correctly recovered to better than 1% on
 scales below 
\begin_inset Formula $k<1h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

 in real space and 
\begin_inset Formula $k<0.5h{\rm Mpc^{-1}}$
\end_inset

 in redshift space.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also consider the frequency with which one must store outputs to construct
 galaxy light cones.
 In real space, a simple linear interpolation over 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta z<0.25$
\end_inset

 recovers the power spectrum to better than 1% for 
\begin_inset Formula $k<1h{\rm Mpc}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 In redshift space, we find we additionally need to interpolate halo velocities.
 Again, linear interpolation recovers the redshift space power spectrum
 to 1% for 
\begin_inset Formula $k<0.8h{\rm Mpc}^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 We conclude that spacings of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta z=0.05$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $0.1$
\end_inset

 are adequate for constructing light cones from single-time snapshots.
 We note that these requirements are significantly less stringent than what
 is required for constructing merger trees, and therefore will often be
 trivially met.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As a demonstration of the utility of the methods presented here, we generate
 a suite of five 
\begin_inset Formula $(4h^{-1}{\rm Gpc})^{3}$
\end_inset

 simulations for a total simulation volume of 320 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{-3}{\rm Gpc}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 We consider two example applications of these.
 The first is the construction of mock galaxy catalogs.
 We focus here on the BOSS CMASS sample, but these simulations may be used
 for future surveys like eBOSS and DESI.
 The second demonstration is to measure the effects of nonlinear evolution
 and galaxy bias on the position of the BAO feature.
 This extends the work of Ref.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "2011ApJ...734...94M"

\end_inset

 with significantly improved statistics.
 We measure a high significance detection (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim6\sigma$
\end_inset

) of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim0.6\%$
\end_inset

 shift in the BAO peak, as well as detecting hints of a dependence on bias
 (for very large values of the bias).
 Both of these examples were chosen to demonstrate the utility of these
 simulations, and will be explored in more detail in future work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above examples are not the only applications of the simulations made
 possible by our approach here.
 For instance, while the volumes of simulations are still not large enough
 to simply measure a sample covariance matrix, such simulations could be
 very useful in calibrating models of covariance matrices.
 Unlike other approximate methods, these simulations are accurate down to
 relatively small scales 
\begin_inset Formula $k\sim1h{\rm Mpc}^{-1}$
\end_inset

, and so are ideal for comparing against models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Large scale suites of simulations are an essential part of current and future
 cosmological analyses.
 This paper helps lay part of the groundwork for how one can optimize the
 computational requirements of such simulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Exploring new diagnostics for the internal structure of clusters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tidal stripping in cluster environments - what is expected theoretically
 and what is seen observationally.
 ** Tidal stripping of cluster galaxies a la Jeff Kenney ** Tidal stripping
 of cluster galaxies from lensing studies (PN 2009, comparison with simulations
 with Springel -- 2 papers) Need to introduce the effect of assembly bias
 and its role in where galaxies end up radially in the cluster Compare simulatio
ns with observations of samples and go beyond individual objects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Summary previous work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Paraphrase More et al.
 papers and their results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Methods & Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Simulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We use the Bolshoi 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "bolshoi_11"

\end_inset

 which were run with the Adaptive Refinement Tree Code 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kravtsov_etal97,gottloeber_klypin08"

\end_inset

 assuming a flat 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda{\rm CDM}$
\end_inset

 model with density parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{m}=0.27$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{\Lambda}=0.73$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega_{b}=0.0469$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{8}=0.82$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0.95$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h=0.70$
\end_inset

.
 The Bolshoi simulation used 
\begin_inset Formula $2048^{3}$
\end_inset

 particles in a 
\begin_inset Formula $250h^{-1}{\rm Mpc}$
\end_inset

 box with a force resolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $1h^{-1}{\rm kpc}$
\end_inset

, giving a particle mass of 
\begin_inset Formula $1.35\times10^{8}h^{-1}{\rm M_{\odot}}$
\end_inset

.
 Dark matter halos and subhalos are identified using the 
\family typewriter
ROCKSTAR
\family default
 phase-space, temporal halo finder 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rockstar"

\end_inset

 and merger trees are constructed using the 
\family typewriter
CONSISTENT TREES 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "rockstar_trees"

\end_inset


\family default
  procedures
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The catalogues used in this paper are publicly available at 
\begin_inset Flex Flex:URL
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

http://hipacc.ucsc.edu/Bolshoi/MergerTrees.html
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 All of the results we consider here are at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In what follows, we use the virial masses and maximum circular velocities
 (tagged 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\family typewriter
mvir
\family default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\family typewriter
vmax
\family default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) directly from the halo catalogues.
 The 
\family typewriter
ROCKSTAR
\family default
 halo finder computes halo masses based on spherical overdensities using
 a threshold of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{{\rm h}}=360$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color red
about host halo and subhalo
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The halo mass and velocity functions start to show incompleteness at 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{10.4}h^{-1}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $\sim200$
\end_inset

 particles) for the Bolshoi simulation.
 Below those masses, the halo mass distributions show unphysical drop-offs
 indicating incomplete mass resolution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to the standard classification of halos into host halos (not
 within the virial radius of a more massive halo) and subhalos (within the
 virial radius of a more massive halo), we further classify host halos into
 ejected and non-ejected halos.
 Ejected halos, also referred to as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

backsplash
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 halos, are host halos whose main progenitor was classified, at some point
 in its merger tree history, as a subhalo.
 As we discuss below, these ejected halos have very different clustering
 properties compared to their non-ejected counterparts.
 The ejected fraction for the Bolshoi simulation is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim15.8\%$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{11}h^{-1}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

, and drops to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sim6.3\%$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $10^{13}h^{-1}M_{\odot}$
\end_inset

.
 The lower mass resolution of the MultiDark simulation prevents us from
 making this additional sub-classification.
 Accordingly, results that rely on this split are restricted to the Bolshoi
 simulation and mass range.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Radial distribution of subhalos in real-space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_Cluster/Bolshoi_M14_radial.pdf
	width 45text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ../plots_Cluster/Bolshoi_M14_radial2.pdf
	width 45text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Left: Radial distribution of subhalos 
\begin_inset Formula $r/R_{{\rm vir}}$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{acc,sub}/M_{host}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.3$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{acc,sub}$
\end_inset

 is subhalo masses at accretion and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{host}$
\end_inset

 is the host halo masses at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.3$
\end_inset

.
 The distributions indicate that more massive subhalos tend to exist closer
 to the center of the host halo.
 Right: Radial distribution of subhalos as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.3$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 are the subhalo masses at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.3$
\end_inset

 and at accretion respectively.
 Having smaller ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{{\rm vir,sub}}/M_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 implies that subhalos lost more masses due to tidal stripping, and those
 subhalos whose masses are more stripped tend to be closer to the center
 of the host halo.
 Note that histograms are normalized.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename /Users/old_ts485/Desktop/my_thesis/plots_Cluster/Bolshoi_M14_subVmax_radial.pdf
	width 50text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Radial distribution of subhalos as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.3$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 are the maximum circular velocities of the subhalos at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0.3$
\end_inset

 and at accretion respectively.
 Having smaller ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{{\rm max,sub}}/V_{{\rm acc,sub}}$
\end_inset

 implies that subhalos lost masses not only from the outer region of the
 subhalos but also frm the core, and those subhalos tend to be closer to
 the center of the host halo.
 Note that histograms are normalized.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

